# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-thorndike
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The science of abnormal psychology studies two types of behaviors: adaptive and maladaptive behaviors.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Maladaptive behaviors suggest that some problem(s) exist and can also imply that the individual is vulnerable and unable to cope with environmental stress, leading to difficulties functioning in daily life across emotions, thinking, physical actions, and speech.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Adaptive behaviors are well-suited to the nature of people, their lifestyles and surroundings, and the people they communicate with, allowing them to understand each other.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Clinical psychology is the applied field of psychology that seeks to assess, understand, and treat psychological conditions in clinical practice.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The theoretical field known as *abnormal psychology* may form a backdrop to such work.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Still, clinical psychologists in the field are unlikely to use the term 'abnormal' in reference to their practice.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Psychopathology is a similar term to abnormal psychology, but may have more of an implication of an underlying pathology (disease process), which assumes the medical model of mental disturbance and as such, is a term more commonly used in the medical specialty known as psychiatry.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates (460–377 BCE) hypothesized that the body and mind become unwell when the so-called humors, vital fluids in the body, become unbalanced.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The four temperaments theory posits four such humors: black bile, yellow bile, phlegm, and blood.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Each humor was associated with a particular temperament: too much phlegm causes a person to be fatigued, too much black bile causes melancholia, yellow bile causes a quick temper, and too much blood causes optimism, cheerfulness, and confidence.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The act of placing individuals with mental illness in a separate facility known as an asylum dates to 1547, when King Henry VIII of England established the St.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This hospital, nicknamed Bedlam, was famous for its deplorable conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Asylums remained popular throughout the Middle Ages and the Renaissance era.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These early asylums often had miserable conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Patients were seen as a "burden" to society, locked away and treated almost like beasts to be dealt with, rather than patients needing treatment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] However, many of the patients received helpful medical treatment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] There was scientific curiosity into abnormal behavior, although it was rarely investigated in the early asylums.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Inmates in these early asylums were often put on display for profit, as they were viewed as less than human.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The early asylums were basically modifications of the existing criminal institutions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In the late 18th century, the idea of humane treatment for patients gained favor due to the work of Philippe Pinel in France.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] He pushed for the idea that the patients should be treated with kindness, and not the cruelty inflicted on them, as if they were animals or criminals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] His experimental ideas, such as removing the chains from the patients, were met with reluctance.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The experiments in kindness proved a great success, helping reform how mental institutions would be run.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Institutionalization would continue to improve throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, as a result of the work of many humanitarians such as Dorothea Dix and the mental hygiene movement, which promoted the physical well-being of people with mental health conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] "Dix, more than any other figure in the nineteenth century, made people in America and virtually all of Europe aware that the insane were being subjected to incredible abuses." Through this movement, millions of dollars were raised to build new institutions to house the mentally ill.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Mental hospitals grew substantially in number during the 20th century as care for the mentally ill increased.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] By 1939, there were over 400,000 patients in state mental hospitals in the US.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Hospital stays were normally quite long for the patients, with some individuals being treated for many years.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These hospitals, while better than the asylums of the past, still lacked the means to provide effective treatment for patients.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Even though the reform movement had occurred, patients were often still met with cruel and inhumane treatment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Things began to change in 1946, when Mary Jane Ward published the influential novel *The Snake Pit*, which was adapted into a popular movie of the same name.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The book called attention to the conditions that people with a mental health condition faced, and helped to spark concern in the general public to create more humane mental health care in these overcrowded hospitals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] That same year, the National Institute of Mental Health was also created, providing support for training hospital employees and research into patients' conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] During this period, the Hill–Burton Act was also passed, a program that funded mental health hospitals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Along with the Community Health Services Act of 1963, the Hill–Burton Acts helped create outpatient psychiatric clinics, inpatient general hospitals, and rehabilitation and community consultation centers.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In the late twentieth century, however, many mental hospitals were closed in many countries.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In England, for example, only 14 of the 130 psychiatric institutions established in the early 20th century remained open at the start of the 21st century.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Kennedy launched the community health movement in the United States as a "bold new approach" to mental health care, aimed at coordinating mental health services for citizens in mental health centers.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Over the span of 40 years, the United States saw about a 90 percent drop in the number of patients in psychiatric hospitals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Deinstitutionalisation ended the long-term confinement of patients in isolating mental hospitals, which could and did cause long-term negative adaptations.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] For instance, institutionalizing people with schizophrenia worsens negative symptoms.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] However, the practice is sometimes criticised for a perceived rise in homelessness amongst people who were previously institutionalized, or are presumed to have been in the institution era.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] People have tried to explain and control abnormal behavior for thousands of years.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Historically, there have been three main approaches to abnormal behavior: the supernatural, biological, and psychological traditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Abnormal psychology revolves around two major paradigms for explaining mental disorders, the *psychological* paradigm and the *biological* paradigm.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The psychological paradigm focuses more on the humanistic, cognitive, and behavioral causes and effects of psychopathology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The biological paradigm includes theories that focus more on physical factors, such as genetics and neurochemistry.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In the first supernatural tradition, also known as the demonological method, abnormal behavior is attributed to agents outside the human body.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] According to this model, abnormal behaviors are caused by demons, aliens, or spirits, or the influences of the Moon, planets, and stars.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] During the Stone Age, trepanning was performed on those who had mental illness, to literally cut the evil spirits out of the victim's head.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Conversely, Ancient Chinese, Ancient Egyptians, and Hebrews believed that these were evil demons or spirits and advocated exorcism.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] By the time of the Greeks and Romans, mental illnesses were thought to be caused by an imbalance of the four humors, which led to treatments such as draining fluids from the brain.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] During the Medieval period, many Europeans believed that the power of witches, demons, and spirits caused abnormal behaviors.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] People with psychological disorders were thought to be possessed by evil spirits that had to be exorcised through religious rituals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] If exorcism failed, some authorities advocated steps such as confinement, beating, and other types of torture to make the body uninhabitable to witches, demons, and spirits.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The belief that witches, demons, and spirits were responsible for abnormal behavior persisted into the 15th century.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Swiss alchemist, astrologer, and physician Paracelsus (1493–1541), on the other hand, rejected the idea that abnormal behaviors were caused by witches, demons, and spirits and suggested that the movements of the moon and stars influenced people's mind and behaviors.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Some people, especially in developing countries, as well as some followers of religious sects in developed countries, continue to believe that supernatural powers influence human behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In Western academia, the supernatural tradition has been largely replaced by the biological and psychological traditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Throughout history, societies have proposed several explanations for abnormal human behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In some hunter-gatherer societies, animists have believed that people exhibiting abnormal behavior are possessed by malevolent spirits.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This idea has been associated with trepanation, the practice of cutting a hole into the individual's skull to release the malevolent spirits.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Although it has been difficult to define abnormal psychology, one definition includes characteristics such as statistical infrequency.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] A more formalized response to spiritual beliefs about abnormality is the practice of exorcism.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Performed by religious authorities, exorcism is thought of as another way to release evil spirits who cause pathological behavior within the person.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In some instances, individuals exhibiting unusual thoughts or behaviors have been exiled from society, or worse.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Perceived witchcraft, for example, has been punished by death.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Two Catholic Inquisitors wrote the *Malleus Maleficarum* (Latin for "The Hammer Against Witches"), which many Inquisitors and witch-hunters used.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] It contained an early taxonomy of perceived deviant behavior and proposed guidelines for prosecuting deviant individuals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In the biological tradition, psychological disorders are attributed to biological causes.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In the psychological tradition, disorders are attributed to faulty psychological development, and to social context.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The medical or biological perspective holds the belief that most or all abnormal behavior can be attributed to a medical factor; assuming all psychological disorders are diseases.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The Greek physician Hippocrates, considered the father of Western medicine, played a major role in the biological tradition.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates and his associates wrote the Hippocratic Corpus between 450 and 350 BC, in which they suggested that abnormal behaviors can be treated like any other disease.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates viewed the brain as the seat of consciousness, emotion, intelligence, and wisdom, and believed that disorders involving these functions would logically be located there.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These ideas of Hippocrates and his associates were later adopted by Galen, the Roman physician.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Galen extended these ideas and developed a strong and influential school of thought within the biological tradition that extended well into the 18th century.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Kendra Cherry, MSEd, states: "The medical approach to abnormal psychology focuses on the biological causes of mental illness.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This perspective emphasizes understanding the underlying cause of disorders, which might include genetic inheritance, related physical disorders, infections, and chemical imbalances.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] According to Sigmund Freud's structural model, the id, ego, and superego are three theoretical constructs that define the way an individual interacts with the external world, as well as responding to internal forces The Id represents the instinctual drives of an individual that remain unconscious.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The superego represents a person's conscience and their internalization of societal norms and morality.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Finally, the ego serves to realistically integrate the id's drives with the superego's prohibitions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Lack of development in the superego, or an incoherently developed Superego within an individual, will result in thoughts and actions that are irrational and abnormal, contrary to the norms and beliefs of society.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Unconscious fears drive irrational beliefs and can result in abnormal behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Rational emotive behavior therapy helps to drive irrational and maladaptive beliefs out of one's mind.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The term sociocultural refers to the various circles of influence on the individual, ranging from close friends and family to the institutions and policies of a country or the world as a whole.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Discriminations, whether based on social class, income, race and ethnicity, or gender, can influence the development of abnormal behaviour.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The number of different theoretical perspectives in the field of psychological abnormality has made it difficult to explain psychopathology properly.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The attempt to explain all mental disorders with the same theory leads to reductionism (explaining a disorder or other complex phenomena using only a single idea or perspective).
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Most mental disorders are composed of several factors, which is why one must take into account several theoretical perspectives when attempting to diagnose or explain a particular behavioral abnormality or mental disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Explaining mental disorders with a combination of theoretical perspectives is known as multiple causality.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The diathesis–stress model emphasizes the importance of applying multiple causality to psychopathology, by stressing that both precipitating causes and predisposing causes cause disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] A precipitating cause is an immediate trigger that instigates a person's action or behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] A predisposing cause is an underlying factor that interacts with the immediate factors to result in a disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Both causes play a key role in the development of a psychological disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] For example, high neuroticism antedates most types of psychopathology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] There is a wide range of mental disorders that are considered to be forms of Abnormal Psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia can be described as a disorder that causes extreme loss of touch with reality.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The Psychotic nature of schizophrenia manifests itself through delusions, as well as auditory and visual hallucinations.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia is known to have a genetic etiology, as well as other biological components, such as brain disruptions in the prenatal development period.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is characterized by high amounts of inattention and hyperactive impulsiveness.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Inattentive symptoms include not listening, careless errors, disorganization, losing personal belongings, becoming easily distracted, and forgetfulness.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of hyperactive impulsiveness include fidgeting, talking excessively, and interrupting others.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Antisocial personality disorder is a cluster of personality traits that lead to specific outcomes and violate others' rights.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These personality traits include callousness, deceitfulness, lack of remorse, apathy, manipulation of others, impulsiveness, and grandiosity.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Additional traits may include superficial charm, sexual promiscuity, and pathological lying.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Dissociative identity disorder (DID) involves one individual having multiple personalities.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Those with DID are described as having multiple selves that each have their own consciousness and awareness.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] DID has two main etiologies, which are the post-traumatic and socio-cognitive models.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The post-traumatic model states that DID is caused by inescapable past trauma, such as child abuse.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The child dissociates and forms alternate personalities as a coping mechanism in response to the current trauma.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Even when the trauma ends, the personalities continue to disrupt the person's life long-term.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The socio-cognitive model states that people implicitly act as if they have multiple personalities to align with cultural norms.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Those with social anxiety disorder (SAD) have a very intense fear of social situations.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This fear stems from the belief that the person will be evaluated negatively or embarrass themselves.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] SAD is also considered to be one of the more disabling mental disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of this disorder include fear in most, if not all, social situations.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] SAD can develop after a traumatic and/or embarrassing experience has occurred while other people were observing the person.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Generalized anxiety disorder is characterized by a constant, chronic state of worry and anxiety that is related to a large variety of situations and is difficult to control.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Additional symptoms may include irritability, fatigue, concentration difficulties, and restlessness.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Individuals with specific phobias have an extreme fear and avoidance of various objects or situations.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Specifically, fears become phobias when there is excessive and unreasonable fear that is disproportionate to the culture that the individual is in.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Examples of specific phobias include, but are not limited to, phobias of school, blood, injury, needles, small animals, and heights.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is described as physical and mental distress related to past traumatic experiences.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] PTSD can manifest a large variety of symptoms, including, but not limited to, nightmares, flashbacks, avoidance, and/or physiological reactions related to stimuli regarding the trauma, shame, guilt, anger, hypervigilance, and social withdrawal.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] PTSD symptoms can arise due to various experiences that involve actual or threatened violence, injury, or death.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Firsthand experience, witnessing, or learning about traumatic experiences can lead to the development of PTSD.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 is the manual that contains the most widely discussed and researched information on this topic.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Various conditions have been included in this manual and continue to be added to the DSM-5.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The causes of many of these diseases stem from genetic, biological, sociocultural, systemic, and biopsychosocial factors.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Various counseling theories support and help explain the findings related to each illness.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In North America, this is the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of the American Psychiatric Association.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The current version of the book is known as the DSM-5.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] It lists a set of disorders and provides detailed descriptions of what constitutes a mental disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 identifies three key elements that must be present to constitute a mental disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 uses three main sections to organize its contents.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Section I includes the introduction, use, and basics of the DSM-5.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Section II includes diagnostic criteria and codes.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Section III includes emerging measures and models.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Section I of the DSM-5 briefly prefaces purpose, content, structure, and use.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This includes basics, introductions, and cautionary statements for forensic use.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Information is also given about the revision and review processes as well as the DSM-5's goals to harmonize with the ICD-11.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] An explanation regarding the change from the previous multi-axial classification system to the current three-section system is also included here.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Section II of the DSM-5 contains a wide range of diagnostic criteria and codes used to establish and diagnose a vast array of abnormal psychological constructs.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These categories are used to organize abnormal psychological concepts based on their similarities.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Section III of the DSM-5 contains the various methods and strategies that are used to make clinical decisions, understand culture, and explore emerging diagnoses.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The major international nosologic system for the classification of mental disorders is the International Classification of Diseases, 10th revision (ICD-10).
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-10 has been used by World Health Organization (WHO) Member States since 1994.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Chapter five covers some 300 mental and behavioral disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The APA's DSM-IV has influenced Chapter 5 of ICD-10, and there is a great deal of concordance between the two.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Beginning in January 2022, the ICD-11 will replace the ICD-10 in WHO member states.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] WHO maintains free access to the ICD-10 Online.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-11 is the most recent version of the International Classification of Diseases.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The *Mental, behavioral, or Neurodevelopmental disorders section* highlights forms of abnormal psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Psychologists may use different perspectives to gain a better understanding of abnormal psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Some of them may concentrate on a single perspective.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] But professionals prefer to combine two or three perspectives to obtain meaningful information for better treatments.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalytic theory is heavily based on the theory of the neurologist Sigmund Freud.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These ideas often represented repressed emotions and memories from a patient's childhood in the patient's unconscious.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] According to psychoanalytic theory, these repressions cause the disturbances people experience in their daily lives, and by finding their source, one should be able to eliminate them.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This is accomplished through a variety of methods, including free association, hypnosis, and insight.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The goal of these methods is to induce a catharsis, or emotional release, in the patient, which should indicate that the source of the problem has been tapped and can then be treated.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Freud's psychosexual stages also played a key role in this form of therapy, as he would often believe that the problems the patient was experiencing were due to them becoming stuck, or "fixated", in a particular stage.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Dreams also played a major role in this form of therapy, as Freud viewed dreams as a way to gain insight into the unconscious mind.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Patients were often asked to keep dream journals to bring in for discussion during the next therapy session.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] There are many potential problems associated with this style of therapy, including resistance to the repressed memory or feeling, and negative transference onto the therapist.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalysis was carried on by many after Freud, including his daughter Anna Freud, and Jacques Lacan.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Many others have also elaborated on Freud's original theory and added their own take on defense mechanisms or dream analysis.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] While psychoanalysis has fallen out of favor to more modern forms of therapy, it is still used by some clinical psychologists to varying degrees.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Behavior therapy relies on the principles of behaviorism, such as involving classical and operant conditioning.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism arose in the early 20th century, from the work of psychologists such as James Watson and B.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism states that all behaviors humans do are because of a stimulus and reinforcement.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] While this reinforcement is normally for good behavior, it can also occur for maladaptive behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In this therapeutic view, the patient's maladaptive behavior has been reinforced, which will lead to its repetition.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The goal of the therapy is to reinforce less maladaptive behaviors so that, over time, these adaptive behaviors become the patient's primary ones.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy aims to achieve self-actualization (Carl Rogers, 1961).
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In this style of therapy, the therapist will focus on the patient themselves rather than on the patient's problem.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The goal of this therapy is, by treating the patient as "human", rather than "client", to get to the source of the problem and to resolve the problem effectively.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy has been on the rise in recent years and is associated with numerous benefits.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] It is considered one of the core elements needed for therapeutic effectiveness and a significant contributor to the well-being of not only the patient but society as a whole.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Some say that all therapeutic approaches today draw on the humanistic approach in some way, and that humanistic therapy is the best way to treat a patient.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy can be used on people of all ages; it is very popular among children in its variant known as "play therapy".
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) aims to influence thought and cognition (Beck, 1977).
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This form of therapy relies on not only the components of behavioral therapy as mentioned before, but also the elements of cognitive psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This relies on not only the clients behavioral problems that could have arisen from conditioning, but also their negative schemas and distorted perceptions of the world around them.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These negative schemas may cause distress in the patient's life; for example, they may lead to unrealistic expectations about how well they should perform at work or how they should look.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] When these expectations are not met, it will often result in maladaptive behaviors, such as depression, obsessive compulsions, and anxiety.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] With CBT, the goal is to change the schemas causing stress in the patient's life and replace them with more realistic ones.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Once the negative schemas have been replaced, this will hopefully lead to remission of the patient's symptoms.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] CBT is considered particularly effective in the treatment of depression and has even been used in recent years in group settings.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] It is felt that using CBT in a group setting aids in giving its members a sense of support and decreasing the likelihood of them dropping out of therapy before the treatment has had time to work properly.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] CBT is an effective treatment for many patients, even those who do not have diseases and disorders typically thought of as psychiatric ones.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] For example, patients with the disease multiple sclerosis have found a lot of help using CBT.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The treatment often helps the patients cope with the disorder they have and how they can adapt to their new lives without developing new problems, such as depression or negative schemas about themselves.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] According to RAND, therapies are difficult to provide to all patients in need.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] A lack of funding and understanding of symptoms provides a major roadblock that is not easily avoided.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Individual symptoms and responses to treatment vary, creating a disconnect among patients, society, and caregivers/professionals.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] In play therapy, the clinicians will "play" with their client, usually with toys or a tea party.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Playing is typical child behavior; therefore, playing with the therapist will come naturally to the child.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] While playing together, the clinician will ask the patient questions, and in this setting, they seem less intrusive, more therapeutic, and more like a normal conversation.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This should help the patient identify their issues and disclose them to the therapist with less difficulty than they may experience in a traditional counseling setting.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy involves a therapist observing a child as the child plays with toys and interacts with their surrounding environment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The therapist plays both an observational and an interactional role in the intervention.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This process allows the child to enact their problems through play and speak more comfortably with the therapist.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Although somewhat controversial, due to data that suggests a lack of effectiveness in children older than 10 years old, play therapy is a valuable treatment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] This therapy is particularly useful for younger children under 10 who are consciously aware of their environment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy is important, given that many therapeutic interventions effective for adults are less effective for children.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapies are based on the belief that children's problems stem from issues within the family.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapy aims to improve relationships among multiple people within specific families through therapeutic intervention.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] For the best effect, it is recommended that the entire family be included in the therapy.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The treatments include family management skill development and child–parent attachment development.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These interventions help to improve family functioning.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Family therapists can teach family management skills, including improving supervision and disciplinary practices and creating environments that foster positive interactions between parents and children.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Child–parent attachment development involves altering or creating relationships between parents and children, in attempts to create secure bases for the child, and to facilitate trust, independence, and positive perceptions of family relationships.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] We see these situations a lot more than we think, which makes some spectrums of abnormal psychology more normal and more common.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] These goals are often achieved by creating understanding regarding behaviors, creating opportunities for attachment, and increasing the family's ability to think about their history and relationships.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] One of the primary criticisms of the term "Abnormal Psychology" is its contribution to the stigmatization of individuals with mental health conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] The label "abnormal" implies a deviation from a societal norm, which can reinforce negative stereotypes and social exclusion.
[src:edward-thorndike/abnormal-psychology] Critics argue that such language can lead to individuals feeling marginalized, perpetuating a sense of "otherness" and reinforcing the stigma associated with mental health issues.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow was a psychology professor at Cornell University, Brooklyn College, Brandeis University, The New School for Social Research, and Columbia University.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He stressed the importance of focusing on the positive qualities in people, as opposed to treating them as a "bag of symptoms".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] A *Review of General Psychology* survey, published in 2002, ranked Maslow as the tenth most cited psychologist of the 20th century.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Born in 1908 and raised in Brooklyn, New York, Maslow was the oldest of seven children.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] His parents were first-generation Jewish immigrants from Kyiv, then part of the Russian Empire (now Kyiv, Ukraine), who fled from Czarist persecution in the early 20th century.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] They had decided to live in New York City and in a multiethnic, working-class neighborhood.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] His parents were poor and not intellectually focused, but they valued education.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He had various encounters with antisemitic gangs who would chase and throw rocks at him.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He eventually developed a strong revulsion towards his mother.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He also grew up with few friends other than his cousin Will, and as a result, he grew up in libraries and among books.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] It was here that he developed his love for reading and learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He went to Boys High School, one of the top high schools in Brooklyn, where his best friend was his cousin Will Maslow.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Here, he served as the officer to many academic clubs and became editor of the Latin magazine.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He also edited *Principia,* the school's physics paper, for a year.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow attended the City College of New York after high school.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1926, he began taking legal studies classes at night in addition to his undergraduate course load.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He disliked it and almost immediately dropped out.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1927, he transferred to Cornell University but left after just one semester due to poor grades and high costs.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He later graduated from City College and went to graduate school at the University of Wisconsin to study psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1928, he married his first cousin, Bertha, who was still in high school.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The pair had met in Brooklyn years earlier.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's psychology training at University of Wisconsin was decidedly experimental-behaviorist.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] At Wisconsin, he pursued a line of research that included investigating primate dominance behavior and sexuality.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's early experience with behaviorism would leave him with a strong positivist mindset.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Upon the recommendation of professor Hulsey Cason, Maslow wrote his master's thesis on "learning, retention, and reproduction of verbal material".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow regarded the research as embarrassingly trivial, but he completed his thesis in the summer of 1931 and was awarded his master's degree in psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He was so ashamed of the thesis that he removed it from the psychology library and tore out its catalog listing.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] However, Cason admired the research enough to urge Maslow to submit it for publication.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's thesis was published as two articles in 1934.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow continued his research on similar themes at Columbia University.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] There he found another mentor in Alfred Adler, one of Sigmund Freud's early colleagues.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] From 1937 to 1951, Maslow was on the faculty of Brooklyn College.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] His family life and his experiences influenced his psychological ideas.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] After World War II, Maslow began to question how psychologists had come to their conclusions, and though he did not completely disagree, he had his own ideas on how to understand the human mind.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He called his new discipline humanistic psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow was already 33 years old and had two children when the United States entered World War II in 1941.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He was thus ineligible for military service.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] However, the war inspired a vision of peace in him, leading to his groundbreaking psychological studies of self-actualizing.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The studies began under the supervision of two mentors, anthropologist Ruth Benedict and Gestalt psychologist Max Wertheimer, whom he admired professionally and personally.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Being such "wonderful human beings" also inspired Maslow to take notes about them and their behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] This would be the basis of his lifelong research and thinking about mental health and human potential.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow extended the subject, borrowing ideas from other psychologists and adding new ones, such as the concepts of a hierarchy of needs, metaneeds, metamotivation, self-actualizing persons, and peak experiences.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He was a professor at Brandeis University from 1951 to 1969.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He became a resident fellow of the Laughlin Institute in California.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1967, Maslow had a serious heart attack and knew his time was limited.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He considered himself to be a psychological pioneer.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He pushed future psychologists by bringing to light different paths to ponder.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He built the framework that later allowed other psychologists to conduct more comprehensive studies.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow believed that leadership should be non-intervening.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Consistent with this approach, he rejected a nomination in 1963 to be the Association for Humanistic Psychology president because he felt the organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] While jogging, Maslow had a severe heart attack and died on June 8, 1970, at the age of 62 in Menlo Park, California.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Most psychologists before him had been concerned with the abnormal and the ill.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He urged people to acknowledge their basic needs before addressing higher needs and ultimately self-actualization.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He wanted to know what constituted positive mental health.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Humanistic psychology gave rise to several different therapies, all guided by the idea that people possess the inner resources for growth and healing and that the point of therapy is to help remove obstacles to individuals' achieving them.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The most famous of these was client-centered therapy developed by Carl Rogers.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Humanistic psychology theory suits people who see the positive side of humanity and believe in free will.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] This theory clearly contrasts with Freud's theory of biological determinism.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Another significant strength is that humanistic psychology theory is compatible with other schools of thought.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's hierarchy is also applicable to other topics, such as finance, economics, or even in history or criminology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Humanist psychology, also coined *positive psychology*, is criticized for its lack of empirical validation and therefore its lack of usefulness in treating specific problems.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] It may also fail to help or diagnose people who have severe mental disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Humanistic psychologists believe that every person has a strong desire to realize their full potential, to reach a level of "self-actualization".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The main point of that new movement, that reached its peak in the 1960s, was to emphasize the positive potential of human beings.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] However, Maslow was highly critical of Freud, since humanistic psychologists did not recognize spirituality as a navigation for our behaviors.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] To prove that humans are not blindly reacting to situations, but trying to accomplish something greater, Maslow studied mentally healthy individuals instead of people with serious psychological issues.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Self-actualizing people indicate a *coherent personality syndrome* and represent optimal psychological health and functioning.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] This informed his theory that a person enjoys "peak experiences", high points in life when the individual is in harmony with themself and their surroundings.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In Maslow's view, self-actualized people can have many peak experiences throughout a day while others have those experiences less frequently.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He believed that psychedelic drugs like LSD and psilocybin can produce peak experiences in the right people under the right circumstances.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Self-actualizing people are more likely to have peak experiences.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In other words, these "peak experiences" or states of flow are the reflections of the realization of one's human potential and represent the height of personality development.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In later writings, Maslow moved to a more inclusive model that allowed for, in addition to intense peak experiences, longer-lasting periods of serene being-cognition that he termed *plateau experiences*.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He borrowed this term from the Indian scientist and yoga practitioner, U.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow stated that the shift from the peak to the plateau experience is related to the natural aging process, in which an individual has a shift in life values about what is actually important in one's life and what is not important.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In spite of the personal significance with the plateau experience, Maslow was not able to conduct a comprehensive study of this phenomenon due to health problems that developed toward the end of his life.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In studying accounts of peak experiences, Maslow identified a manner of thought he called "being-cognition" (or "B-cognition"), which is holistic and accepting, as opposed to the evaluative "deficiency-cognition" (or "D-cognition"), and values he called "Being-values".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow described human needs as ordered in a prepotent hierarchy—a pressing need would need to be mostly satisfied before someone would give their attention to the next highest need.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] None of his published works included a visual representation of the hierarchy.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The pyramidal diagram illustrating the Maslow needs hierarchy may have been created by a psychology textbook publisher as an illustrative device.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] This now iconic pyramid frequently depicts the spectrum of human needs, both physical and psychological, as accompaniment to articles describing Maslow's needs theory and may give the impression that the hierarchy of needs is a fixed and rigid sequence of progression.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Yet, starting with the first publication of his theory in 1943, Maslow described human needs as being relatively fluid—with many needs being present in a person simultaneously.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The hierarchy of human needs model suggests that human needs will only be fulfilled one level at a time.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] According to Maslow's theory, when a human being ascends the levels of the hierarchy having fulfilled the needs in the hierarchy, one may eventually achieve self-actualization.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Late in life, Maslow came to conclude that self-actualization was not an automatic outcome of satisfying the other human needs.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The first four levels are known as *deficit needs* or *D-needs*.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] This means that if there are not enough of one of those four needs, there will be a need to get it.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Getting them brings a feeling of contentment.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow wrote that there are certain conditions that must be fulfilled in order for the basic needs to be satisfied.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] For example, freedom of speech, freedom to express oneself, and freedom to seek new information are a few of the prerequisites.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Any blockages of these freedoms could prevent the satisfaction of the basic needs.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's hierarchy is used in higher education for advising students and for student retention as well as a key concept in student development.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's hierarchy has been subject to internet memes over the past few years, specifically looking at the modern integration of technology in people's lives and humorously suggesting that Wi-Fi was among the most basic of human needs.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow defined *self-actualization* as achieving the fullest use of one's talents and interests—the need "to become everything that one is capable of becoming".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] As implied by its name, self-actualization is highly individualistic and reflects Maslow's premise that the self is "sovereign and inviolable" and entitled to "his or her own tastes, opinions, values, etc." Indeed, some have characterized self-actualization as "healthy narcissism".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow realized that the self-actualizing individuals he studied had similar personality traits.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow selected individuals based on his subjective view of them as self-actualized people.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Some of the people he studied included Thomas Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln, and Eleanor Roosevelt.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] They were also "problem centered", meaning that they treated life's difficulties as problems that demanded solutions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] These individuals also were comfortable being alone and had healthy personal relationships.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] They had only a few close friends and family rather than a large number of shallow relationships.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Self-actualizing people tend to focus on problems outside themselves; have a clear sense of what is true and what is false; are spontaneous and creative; and are not bound too strictly by social conventions.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow noticed that self-actualized individuals had a better insight of reality, deeply accepted themselves, others and the world, and also had faced many problems and were known to be impulsive people.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] These self-actualized individuals were very independent and private when it came to their environment and culture, especially their very own individual development on "potentialities and inner resources".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow based his theory partially on his own assumptions about human potential and partially on his case studies of historical figures whom he believed to be self-actualized, including Albert Einstein and Henry David Thoreau.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Consequently, Maslow argued, the way in which essential needs are fulfilled is just as important as the needs themselves.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Together, these define the human experience.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] To the extent a person finds cooperative social fulfillment, he establishes meaningful relationships with other people and the larger world.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In other words, he establishes meaningful connections to an external reality—an essential component of self-actualization.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In contrast, to the extent that vital needs find selfish and competitive fulfillment, a person acquires hostile emotions and limited external relationships—his awareness remains internal and limited.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow used the term metamotivation to describe self-actualized people who are driven by innate forces beyond their basic needs, so that they may explore and reach their full human potential.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's theory of motivation gave insight on individuals having the ability to be motivated by a calling, mission or life purpose.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] It is noted that metamotivation may also be connected to what Maslow called B-(being) creativity, which is a creativity that comes from being motivated by a higher stage of growth.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Another type of creativity that was described by Maslow is known as D-(deficiency) creativity, which suggests that creativity results from an individual's need to fill a gap that is left by an unsatisfied primary need or the need for assurance and acceptance.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow based his study on the writings of other psychologists, Albert Einstein, and people he knew who [he felt] clearly met the standard of self-actualization.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow used Einstein's writings and accomplishments to exemplify the characteristics of the self-actualized person.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Ruth Benedict and Max Wertheimer work was also very influential to Maslow's models of self-actualization.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In this case, from a quantitative-sciences perspective there are numerous problems with this particular approach, which has caused much criticism.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] First, it could be argued that biographical analysis as a method is extremely subjective as it is based entirely on the opinion of the researcher.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Personal opinion is always prone to bias, which reduces the validity of any data obtained.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Therefore, Maslow's operational definition of Self-actualization must not be uncritically accepted as quantitative fact.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] During the 1960s Maslow founded with Stanislav Grof, Viktor Frankl, James Fadiman, Anthony Sutich, Miles Vich and Michael Murphy, the school of transpersonal psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow had concluded that humanistic psychology was incapable of explaining all aspects of human experience.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He identified various mystical, ecstatic, or spiritual states known as "peak experiences" as experiences beyond self-actualization.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow called these experiences "a fourth force in psychology", which he named transpersonal psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Transpersonal psychology was concerned with the "empirical, scientific study of, and responsible implementation of the finding relevant to, becoming, mystical, ecstatic, and spiritual states" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1962, Maslow published a collection of papers on this theme, which developed into his 1968 book *Toward a Psychology of Being*.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In this book Maslow stresses the importance of transpersonal psychology to human beings, writing: "without the transpersonal, we get sick, violent, and nihilistic, or else hopeless and apathetic" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Human beings, he came to believe, need something bigger than themselves that they are connected to in a naturalistic sense, but not in a religious sense: Maslow himself was an atheist and found it difficult to accept religious experience as valid unless placed in a positivistic framework.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In fact, Maslow's position on God and religion was quite complex.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] While he rejected organized religion and its beliefs, he wrote extensively on the human being's need for the sacred and spoke of God in more philosophical terms, as beauty, truth and goodness, or as a force or a principle.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Awareness of transpersonal psychology became widespread within psychology, and the *Journal of Transpersonal Psychology* was founded in 1969, a year after Abraham Maslow became the president of the American Psychological Association.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In the United States, transpersonal psychology encouraged recognition for non-western psychologies, philosophies, and religions, and promoted understanding of "higher states of consciousness", for instance through intense meditation.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Transpersonal psychology has been applied in many areas, including transpersonal business studies.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow called his work positive psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Since 1968 his work has influenced the development of positive psychotherapy, a transcultural, humanistic based psychodynamic psychotherapy method used in mental health and psychosomatic treatment founded by Nossrat Peseschkian.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Since 1999 Maslow's work enjoyed a revival of interest and influence among leaders of the positive psychology movement such as Martin Seligman.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] This movement focuses only on a higher human nature.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Positive psychology spends its research looking at the positive side of things and how they go right rather than the pessimistic side.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1966, Maslow published a pioneering work in the psychology of science, *The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance*, the first book ever actually titled 'psychology of science'.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In this book Maslow proposed a model of 'characterologically relative' science, which he characterized as an ardent opposition to the *historically, philosophically, sociologically and psychologically naıve* positivistic reluctance to see science *relative to time, place, and local culture*.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Abraham Maslow is also known for Maslow's hammer, popularly phrased as "if all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail" from his book *The Psychology of Science*, published in 1966.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's ideas have been criticized for their lack of scientific rigor.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He was criticized as too soft scientifically by American empiricists.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 2006, author and former philosophy professor Christina Hoff Sommers and practicing psychiatrist Sally Satel asserted that, due to lack of empirical support, Maslow's ideas have fallen out of fashion and are "no longer taken seriously in the world of academic psychology".
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Positive psychology spends much of its research looking for how things go right rather than the more pessimistic view point, how things go wrong.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The hierarchy of needs has furthermore been accused of having a cultural bias—mainly reflecting Western values and ideologies.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] From the perspective of many cultural psychologists, this concept is considered relative to each culture and society and cannot be universally applied.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] — Maslow, 'Motivation and Personality' (1970), p.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's concept of self-actualizing people was united with Piaget's developmental theory to the process of initiation in 1993.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow's theory of self-actualization has been met with significant resistance.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The theory itself is crucial to the humanistic branch of psychology and yet it is widely misunderstood.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The concept behind self-actualization is widely misunderstood and subject to frequent scrutiny.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow was criticized for noting too many exceptions to his theory.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] As he acknowledged these exceptions, he did not do much to account for them.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Shortly prior to his death, one problem he tried to resolve was that there are people who have satisfied their deficiency needs but still do not become self-actualized.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] He never resolved this inconsistency within his theory.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Social psychologist David Myers has pointed out Maslow's selection bias, rooted in the choice to study individuals who lived out his own values.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] If he had studied other historical heroes, such as Napoleon, Alexander the Great, and John D.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Rockefeller, his descriptions of self-actualization might have been significantly different.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Later in life, Maslow was concerned with questions such as, "Why don't more people self-actualize if their basic needs are met?
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In the spring of 1961, Maslow and Tony Sutich founded the *Journal of Humanistic Psychology*, with Miles Vich as editor until 1971.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] The journal printed its first issue in early 1961 and continues to publish academic papers.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] Maslow attended the Association for Humanistic Psychology's founding meeting in 1963 where he declined nomination as its president, arguing that the new organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader which resulted in useful strategy during the field's early years.
[src:edward-thorndike/abraham-maslow] In 1967, Maslow was named Humanist of the Year by the American Humanist Association.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He also founded the science of anthropometry and developed the body mass index (BMI) scale, originally called the Quetelet Index.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] His work on measuring human characteristic to determine the ideal *l'homme moyen* ("the average man"), played a key role in the origins of eugenics.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe was born in Ghent (which, at the time was a part of the new French Republic).
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He was the son of François-Augustin-Jacques-Henri Quetelet, a Frenchman and Anne Françoise Vandervelde, a Flemish woman.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] His father was born at Ham, Picardy, and being of a somewhat adventurous spirit, he crossed the English Channel and became both a British citizen and the secretary of a Scottish nobleman.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In that capacity, he traveled with his employer on the Continent, particularly spending time in Italy.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] At about 31, he settled in Ghent and was employed by the city, where Adolphe was born, the fifth of nine children, several of whom died in childhood.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Francois died when Adolphe was only seven years old.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe studied at the Ghent Lycée, where he afterwards started teaching mathematics in 1815 at the age of 19.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1819, he moved to the Athenaeum in Brussels and in the same year he completed his dissertation (*De quibusdam locis geometricis, necnon de curva focal – Of some new properties of the focal distance and some other curves*).
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet received a doctorate in mathematics in 1819 from the University of Ghent.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Shortly thereafter, the young man set out to convince government officials and private donors to build an astronomical observatory in Brussels; he succeeded in 1828.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He became a member of the Royal Academy in 1820.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He lectured at the museum for sciences and letters and at the Belgian Military School.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1825, he became a correspondent of the Royal Institute of the Netherlands, in 1827 he became a member.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1839, he was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] From 1841 to 1851, he was a supernumerary associate in the institute, and when it became Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences he became foreign member.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1850, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1825, he married Cécile-Virginie Curtet.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet also founded several statistical journals and societies, and was especially interested in creating international cooperation among statisticians.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He encouraged the creation of a statistical section of the British Association for the Advancement of Science (BA), which later became the Royal Statistical Society, of which he became the first overseas member.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1853 he chaired both the International Maritime Conference and the first International Statistical Congress.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He was a founding member of the first *Société des douze*.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In 1855, Quetelet developed apoplexy, which diminished but did not end his scientific activity.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He died in Brussels on 17 February 1874, and is buried in the Brussels Cemetery.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] His scientific research encompassed a wide range of different scientific disciplines: meteorology, astronomy, mathematics, statistics, demography, sociology, criminology and history of science.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He made significant contributions to scientific development, but he also wrote several monographs directed to the general public.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He founded the Royal Observatory of Belgium, founded or co-founded several national and international statistical societies and scientific journals, and presided over the first series of the International Statistical Congresses.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was a liberal and an anticlerical, but not an atheist or materialist nor a socialist.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe Quetelet discovered the optical phenomenon Quetelet rings.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] The new science of probability and statistics was mainly used in astronomy at the time, where it was essential to account for measurement errors around means.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] This was done using the method of least squares.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was among the first to apply statistics to social science, planning what he called "social physics".
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He was keenly aware of the overwhelming complexity of social phenomena, and the many variables that needed measurement.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] His goal was to understand the statistical laws underlying such phenomena as crime rates, marriage rates or suicide rates.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He wanted to explain the values of these variables by other social factors.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] These ideas were rather controversial among other scientists at the time who held that it contradicted the concept of freedom of choice.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] His most influential book was *Sur l'homme et le développement de ses facultés, ou Essai de physique sociale*, published in 1835 (In English translation, it is titled *Treatise on Man*, but a literal translation would be "On Man and the Development of his Faculties, or Essay on Social Physics").
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In it, he outlines the project of a social physics and describes his concept of the "average man" (*l'homme moyen*) who is characterized by the mean values of measured variables that follow a normal distribution.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He collected data about many such variables.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet wrote about these values as "ideals" with deviations from them as being less than or more than ideal.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] He saw the average body as an ideal beauty and something to be desired and his work was influential on Francis Galton who coined the term *eugenics*.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet's student Pierre François Verhulst developed the logistic function in the 1830s as a model of population growth; see Logistic function § History for details.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe Quetelet also had a significant influence on Florence Nightingale who shared with him a religious view of statistics which saw understanding statistics as revealing the work of God in addition to statistics being a force of good administration.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Nightingale met Quetelet in person at the 1860 International Statistical Congress in London, and they corresponded for years afterwards.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was an influential figure in criminology.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Along with Andre-Michel Guerry, he helped to establish the cartographic school and positivist schools of criminology which made extensive use of statistical techniques.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Through statistical analysis, Quetelet gained insight into the relationships between crime and other social factors.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Among his findings were strong relationships between age and crime, as well as gender and crime.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Other influential factors he found included climate, poverty, education, and alcohol consumption, with his research findings published in *Of the Development of the Propensity to Crime*.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In his 1835 text on social physics, he presented his theory of human variance around the average, showing human traits were distributed according to a normal curve.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] The existence of such variation provided the basis for later writers, including Darwin, to argue that natural populations contained sufficient variability for artificial or natural selection to operate.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] In terms of influence over later public health agendas, one of Quetelet's lasting legacies was the establishment of a simple measure for classifying people's weight relative to an ideal for their height.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] His proposal, the body mass index (or Quetelet index), has endured with minor variations to the present day.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Anthropometric data is used in modern applications and referenced in the development of every consumer-based product.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 1839.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] The asteroid 1239 Queteleta is named after him.
[src:edward-thorndike/adolphe-quetelet] The title of Quetelet professor at Columbia University is awarded in his name.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The term "affective neuroscience" was coined by neuroscientist Jaak Panksepp in the early 1990s, at a time when cognitive neuroscience focused on parts of psychology that did not include emotion, such as attention or memory.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Emotions are thought to be related to activity in brain areas that direct our attention, motivate our behavior, and help us make decisions about our environment.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Early stages of research on emotions and the brain was conducted by Paul Broca, James Papez, and Paul D.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Their work suggests that emotion is related to a group of structures in the center of the brain called the limbic system.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Research has shown the limbic system is directly related to emotion, but there are other brain areas and structures that are important for producing and processing emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Many theories about the role of the right hemisphere in emotion has resulted in several models of emotional functioning.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] After observing decreased emotional processing after right hemisphere injuries, C.K.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Mills hypothesized emotions are directly related to the right hemisphere.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In 1992, researchers found that emotional expression and understanding may be controlled by smaller brain structures in the right hemisphere.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] These findings were the basis for the right hemisphere hypothesis and the valence hypothesis.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] It is believed that the right hemisphere is more specialized in processing emotions than the left hemisphere.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The right hemisphere is associated with nonverbal, synthetic, integrative, holistic and gestaltic mental strategies.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] As demonstrated by patients who have increased spatial neglect when damage affects the right brain rather than the left brain, the right hemisphere is more connected to subcortical systems of autonomic arousal and attention.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Right hemisphere disorders have been associated with abnormal patterns of autonomic nervous system responses.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] These findings suggest the right hemisphere and subcortical brain areas are closely related.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] According to the valence hypothesis, although the right hemisphere is involved in emotion, it is primarily involved in the processing of negative emotions, while the left hemisphere is involved in processing positive emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In one explanation, negative emotions are processed by the right brain, while positive emotions are processed by the left.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] An alternative explanation is that the right hemisphere is dominant when it comes to feeling both positive and negative emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Recent studies indicate that the frontal lobes of both hemispheres play an active role in emotions, while the parietal and temporal lobes process them.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Depression has been associated with decreased right parietal lobe activity, while anxiety has been associated with increased right parietal lobe activity.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Based on the original valence model, increasingly complex models have been developed as a result of the increasing understanding of the different hemispheres.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] While emotions are integral to thought processes, cognition has been investigated without emotion until the late 1990s, focusing instead on non-emotional processes such as memory, attention, perception, problem solving, and mental imagery.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Cognitive neuroscience and affective neuroscience have emerged as separate fields for studying the neural basis of non-emotional and emotional processes.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Despite the fact that fields are classified according to how the brain processes cognition and emotion, the neural and mental mechanisms behind emotional and non-emotional processes often overlap.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Emotion go/no-go tasks are used to study behavioral inhibition, especially how it is influenced by emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] A "go" cue tells the participant to respond rapidly, but a "no-go" cue tells them to withhold a response.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Because the "go" cue occurs more frequently, it can be used to measure how well a subject suppresses a response under different emotional conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This task is often used in combination with neuroimaging in healthy individuals and patients with affective disorders to identify relevant brain functions associated with emotional regulation.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Several studies, including go/no-go studies, suggest that sections of the prefrontal cortex are involved in controlling emotional responses to stimuli during inhibition.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Adapted from the Stroop, the emotional Stroop test measures how much attention you pay to emotional stimuli.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In this task, participants are instructed to name the ink color of words while ignoring their meanings.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Generally, people have trouble detaching their attention from words with an affective meaning compared with neutral words.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] It has been demonstrated in several studies that naming the color of neutral words results in a quicker response.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Selective attention to negative or threatening stimuli, which are often related to psychological disorders, is commonly tested with this task.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Different mental disorders have been associated with specific attentional biases.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Participants with spider phobia, for example, tend to be more inclined to use spider-related words than negatively charged words.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Similar findings have been found for threat words related to other anxiety disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Even so, other studies have questioned these conclusions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] When the words are matched for emotionality, anxious participants in some studies show the Stroop interference effect for both negative and positive words.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In other words, the specificity effects of words for various disorders may be primarily due to their conceptual relation to the disorder's concerns rather than their emotionality.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The Ekman faces task is used to measure emotion recognition of six basic emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Black and white photographs of 10 actors (6 male, 4 female) are presented, with each actor displaying each emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Participants are usually asked to respond quickly with the name of the displayed emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The task is a common tool to study deficits in emotion regulation in patients with dementia, Parkinson's, and other cognitively degenerative disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The task has been used to analyze recognition errors in disorders such as borderline personality disorder, schizophrenia, and bipolar disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The emotional dot-probe paradigm is a task used to assess selective visual attention to and failure to detach attention from affective stimuli.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The paradigm begins with a fixation cross at the center of a screen.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] An emotional stimulus and a neutral stimulus appear side by side, after which a dot appears behind either the neutral stimulus (incongruent condition) or the affective stimulus (congruent condition).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Participants are asked to indicate when they see this dot, and response latency is measured.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Dots that appear on the same side of the screen as the image the participant was looking at will be identified more quickly.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Thus, it is possible to discern which object the participant was attending to by subtracting the reaction time to respond to congruent versus incongruent trials.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The best documented research with the dot probe paradigm involves attention to threat related stimuli, such as fearful faces, in individuals with anxiety disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Anxious individuals tend to respond more quickly to congruent trials, which may indicate vigilance to threat and/or failure to detach attention from threatening stimuli.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] A specificity effect of attention has also been noted, with individuals attending selectively to threats related to their particular disorder.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] For example, those with social phobia selectively attend to social threats but not physical threats.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] However, this specificity may be even more nuanced.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Participants with obsessive-compulsive disorder symptoms initially show attentional bias to compulsive threat, but this bias is attenuated in later trials due to habituation to the threat stimuli.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Fear-potentiated startle (FPS) has been utilized as a psychophysiological index of fear reaction in both animals and humans.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] FPS is most often assessed through the magnitude of the eyeblink startle reflex, which can be measured by electromyography.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This eyeblink reflex is an automatic defensive reaction to an abrupt elicitor, making it an objective indicator of fear.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Typical FPS paradigms involve bursts of noise or abrupt flashes of light transmitted while an individual attends to a set of stimuli.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Startle reflexes have been shown to be modulated by emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] For example, healthy participants tend to show enhanced startle responses while viewing negatively valenced images and attenuated startle while viewing positively valenced images, as compared with neutral images.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The startle response to a particular stimulus is greater under conditions of threat.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] A common example given to indicate this phenomenon is that one's startle response to a flash of light will be greater when walking in a dangerous neighborhood at night than it would under safer conditions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In laboratory studies, the threat of receiving shock is enough to potentiate startle, even without any actual shock.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Fear potentiated startle paradigms are often used to study fear learning and extinction in individuals with post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) and other anxiety disorders.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In fear conditioning studies, an initially neutral stimulus is repeatedly paired with an aversive one, borrowing from classical conditioning.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] FPS studies have demonstrated that PTSD patients have enhanced startle responses during both danger cues and neutral/safety cues as compared with healthy participants.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Affect plays many roles during learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Deep, emotional attachment to a subject area allows a deeper understanding of the material and therefore, learning occurs and lasts.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The emotions evoked when reading in comparison to the emotions portrayed in the content affects comprehension.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Someone who is feeling sad understands a sad passage better than someone feeling happy.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Therefore, a student's emotion plays an important role during the learning process.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Emotion can be embodied or perceived from words read on a page or in a facial expression.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Neuroimaging studies using fMRI have demonstrated that the same area of the brain that is activated when feeling disgust is activated when observing another's disgust.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In a traditional learning environment, the teacher's facial expression can play a critical role in language acquisition.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Showing a fearful facial expression when reading passages that contain fearful tones facilitates students learning of the meaning of certain vocabulary words and comprehension of the passage.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The neurobiological basis of emotion is still disputed.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The existence of basic emotions and their defining attributes represents a long lasting and yet unsettled issue in psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The available research suggests that the neurobiological existence of basic emotions is still tenable and heuristically seminal, pending some reformulation.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] These approaches hypothesize that emotion categories (including happiness, sadness, fear, anger, and disgust) are biologically basic.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In this view, emotions are inherited, biologically based modules that cannot be separated into more basic psychological components.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Models following this approach hypothesize that all mental states belonging to a single emotional category can be consistently and specifically localized to either a single brain region or a defined network of brain regions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Each basic emotion category also shares other universal characteristics: distinct facial behavior, physiology, subjective experience and accompanying thoughts and memories.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This approach to emotion hypothesizes that emotions like happiness, sadness, fear, anger and disgust (and many others) are constructed mental states that occur when brain systems work together.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In this view, networks of brain regions underlie psychological operations (e.g., language, attention, etc.) that interact to produce emotion, perception, and cognition.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] One psychological operation critical for emotion is the network of brain regions that underlie valence (feeling pleasant/unpleasant) and arousal (feeling activated and energized).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Emotions emerge when neural systems underlying different psychological operations interact (not just those involved in valence and arousal), producing distributed patterns of activation across the brain.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Because emotions emerge from more basic components, heterogeneity affects each emotion category; for example, a person can experience many different kinds of fear, which feel differently, and which correspond to different neural patterns in the brain.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] People typically associate aging with a decline in the functioning of all mental processing abilities; however, this is not the case for emotion regulation.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Older adults typically have a stronger drive to maintain and improve on their emotional well being.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Thus providing them to utilize emotion regulation skills that provide a higher satisfaction in life.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The ventromedial prefrontal cortex (vmPFC) has a significant influence on emotion regulation, especially regarding high emotional arousing stimuli.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Compared to other areas of the prefrontal cortex (PFC), the vmPFC loses volume at a much lower rate.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Due to this, an older person's emotional regulation abilities are not heavily impacted by brain changes associated with aging.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Additionally, the anterior cingulate cortex (ACC) is an important area of the brain that is used for emotion regulation.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The ACC has proven to be a key player in emotion regulation in not just young adults, but also in older adults.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In older adults the ACC is important to create connections with from the vmPFC in order to regulate emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This connection was the most salient when negative emotions were reappraised.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This demonstrates that older adults use the vmPFC to regulate their emotions in a more positive manner.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Despite other areas of the brain decreasing in functionality as humans age, the connection between the vmPFC and ACC remains strong to reappraise negative emotions into more positive emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This is different from younger adults, who rely more on other areas of the PFC.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] As people age, most cognitive functions decline.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This is not the case when it comes to emotion regulation.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] A study conducted by Carstensen and colleagues (2000) found that as people increase in age so does their ability to regulate their emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Just because older adults had better emotion regulation skills, does not mean they live more stable daily lives.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In fact, they tend to have more unstable negative emotions especially in comparison to the stability of their positive emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The major difference observed in how older adults and younger adults regulate their emotions when negative emotional stimuli are present can be explained by numerous theories.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] How older adults handle emotionally salient events or stimuli are often vastly different from younger adults, and even middle aged adults.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] There does not appear to be many differences in ways that younger, middle, and older adults handle social situations; however, when a social situation becomes emotionally charged differences emerge.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] When intense emotions in a social situation were evoked for older adults, they tended to the situation in a more passive manner in comparison to middle aged adults.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] They also tend to rely more on their previous problem solving skills than both younger and older adults.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This is because as people age, there tends to be a shift in preferences to maintain a more positive emotional affect.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In fact, there seems to be a decrease in negative emotions felt by older adults once until they reach the age of 60, in which this decrease stops.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] While the frequency of negative emotion decreases with age, the intensity of the emotions experienced does not change.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Additionally, emotional satisfaction is not lower just because they experience less frequent negative emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Carstensen (2003) hypothesized that the reason that older adults tended to have better emotion regulation skills than younger adults is due to the socioemotional selectivity theory.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This theory highlights the role of social interactions in the ability to regulate emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Social interactions, while are often positive, can sometimes lead to negative emotional arousal.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Since older adults have been alive longer, they have more dense social networks.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This creates a drastic increase in social interaction that cause positive emotional arousal.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] On the chance they experience a negative emotional reaction from a social event, they are likely to be able to pair it with something that is more positively emotionally salient.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This causes the negative emotion to be less potent, and therefore increase their hedonic perspective on life.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] A meta-analysis is a statistical approach to synthesizing results across multiple studies.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Included studies investigated healthy, unmedicated adults and that used subtraction analysis to examine brain areas that were more active during emotional processing than during a neutral (control) condition.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In the first neuroimaging meta-analysis of emotion, Phan et al.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] (2002) analyzed the results of 55 peer reviewed studies between January 1990 and December 2000 to determine if the emotions of fear, sadness, disgust, anger, and happiness were consistently associated with activity in specific brain regions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] All studies used fMRI or PET techniques to investigate higher-order mental processing of emotion (studies of low-order sensory or motor processes were excluded).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The authors' tabulated the number of studies that reported activation in specific brain regions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] For each brain region, statistical chi-squared analysis was conducted.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Two regions showed a statistically significant association.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In the amygdala, 66% of studies inducing fear reported activity in this region, as compared to ~20% of studies inducing happiness, ~15% of studies inducing sadness (with no reported activations for anger or disgust).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In the subcallosal cingulate, 46% of studies inducing sadness reported activity in this region, as compared to ~20% inducing happiness and ~20% inducing anger.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This pattern of clear discriminability between emotion categories was in fact rare, with other patterns occurring in limbic regions, paralimbic regions, and uni/heteromodal regions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Brain regions implicated across discrete emotion included the basal ganglia (~60% of studies inducing happiness and ~60% of studies inducing disgust reported activity in this region) and medial prefrontal cortex (happiness ~60%, anger ~55%, sadness ~40%, disgust ~40%, and fear ~30%).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] 2003 analyzed 106 peer reviewed studies published between January 1994 and December 2001 to examine the evidence for regional specialization of discrete emotions (fear, disgust, anger, happiness and sadness) across a larger set of studies.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Studies included in the meta-analysis measured activity in the whole brain and regions of interest (activity in individual regions of particular interest to the study).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] 3-D Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS3) statistics were used to compare rough spatial distributions of 3-D activation patterns to determine if statistically significant activations were specific to particular brain regions for all emotional categories.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This pattern of consistently activated, regionally specific activations was identified in four brain regions: amygdala with fear (~40% of studies), insula with disgust (~70%), globus pallidus with disgust (~70%), and lateral orbitofrontal cortex with anger (80%).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Other regions showed different patterns of activation across categories.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] For example, both the dorsal medial prefrontal cortex and the rostral anterior cingulate cortex showed consistent activity across emotions (happiness ~50%, sadness ~50%, anger ~ 40%, fear ~30%, and disgust ~ 20%).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] 2006 examined 161 studies published between 1990 and 2001.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The authors compared the consistency and specificity of prior meta-analytic findings specific to each notional basic emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Consistent neural patterns were defined by brain regions showing increased activity for a specific emotion (relative to a neutral control condition), regardless of the method of induction used (for example, visual vs. auditory cue).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Specific neural patterns were defined as separate circuits for one emotion vs. the other emotions (for example, the fear circuit must be discriminable from the anger circuit, although both may include common brain regions).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In general, the results supported Phan et al. and Murphy et al., but not specificity.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Consistency was determined through the comparison of chi-squared analyses that revealed whether the proportion of studies reporting activation during one emotion was significantly higher than the proportion of studies reporting activation during the other emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Specificity was determined through the comparison of emotion-category brain-localizations by contrasting activations in key regions that were specific to particular emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Increased amygdala activation during fear was the most consistently reported across induction methods (but not specific).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Both meta-analyses associated the anterior cingulate cortex with sadness, although this finding was less consistent (across induction methods) and was not specific.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Both meta-analyses found that disgust was associated with the basal ganglia, but these findings were neither consistent nor specific.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Neither consistent nor specific activity was observed across the meta-analyses for anger or happiness.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This meta-analysis introduced the concept of the basic, irreducible elements of emotional life as dimensions such as approach and avoidance.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Kober reviewed 162 neuroimaging studies published between 1990 and 2005 in order to determine if specific brain regions were activated when experiencing an emotion directly and (indirectly) through the experience of someone else.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] According to the study, six different functional groups showed similar activation patterns.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The psychological functions of each group were discussed in more basic terms.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] These regions may also play a role in processing visual information and paying attention to emotional signals.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] 2010 examined 83 neuroimaging studies published between 1993–2008 to examine whether neuroimaging evidence supports biologically discrete, basic emotions (i.e. fear, anger, disgust, happiness, and sadness).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Consistency analyses identified brain regions associated with individual emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Discriminability analyses identified brain regions that were differentially active under contrasting pairs of emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This meta-analysis examined PET or fMRI studies that reported whole brain analyses identifying significant activations for at least one of the five emotions relative to a neutral or control condition.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The authors used activation likelihood estimation (ALE) to perform spatially sensitive, voxel-wise (sensitive to the spatial properties of voxels) statistical comparisons across studies.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] This technique allows for direct statistical comparison between activation maps associated with each discrete emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Thus, discriminability between the five discrete emotion categories was assessed on a more precise spatial scale than in prior meta-analyses.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Consistency was first assessed by comparing the cross-study ALE map for each emotion to ALE maps generated by random permutations.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Discriminability was assessed by pair-wise contrasts of emotion maps.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Consistent and discriminable activation patterns were observed for the five categories.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Lindquist, et al. reviewed 91 PET and fMRI studies published between January 1990 and December 2007.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] Induction methods were used to elicit fear, sadness, disgust, anger, and happiness.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The goal was to compare basic emotions approaches with psychological constructionist approaches.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] It was found that many brain regions activated consistently or selectively for one emotion category when experienced or perceived.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] As predicted by constructionist models, no region demonstrated functional specificity for fear, disgust, happiness, sadness, or anger.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The authors suggest that certain brain areas traditionally assigned to certain emotions are incorrect and instead correspond to different emotion categories.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] There is some evidence that the amygdala, anterior insula, and orbitofrontal cortex all contribute to "core affect", which are feelings of pleasure or discomfort.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] The anterior cingulate and the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex play a key role in attention, which is closely related to core affect.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] By using sensory information, the anterior cingulate directs attention and motor responses.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] According to psychological constructionist theory, emotions are conceptualizations connecting the world and the body, and the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex facilitates executive attention.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] As well as playing an active role in conceptualizing, the prefrontal cortex and hippocampus also simulate previous experiences.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-neuroscience] In several studies, the ventrolateral prefrontal cortex, which supports language, was consistently active during emotion perception and experience.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] An increasing interest in emotion can be seen in the behavioral, biological and social sciences.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Research over the last two decades suggests that many phenomena, ranging from individual cognitive processing to social and collective behavior, cannot be understood without taking into account affective determinants (i.e. motives, attitudes, moods, and emotions).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] In particular affective science includes psychology, affective neuroscience, sociology, psychiatry, anthropology, ethology, archaeology, economics, criminology, law, political science, history, geography, education and linguistics.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Research is also informed by contemporary philosophical analysis and artistic explorations of emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Emotions developed in human history cause organisms to react to environmental stimuli and challenges.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] The major challenge for this interdisciplinary domain is to integrate research focusing on the same phenomenon, emotion and similar affective processes, starting from different perspectives, theoretical backgrounds, and levels of analysis.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] As a result, one of the first challenges of affective science is to reach consensus on the definition of emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Discussion is ongoing as to whether emotions are primarily bodily responses or whether cognitive processing is central.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Controversy also concerns the most effective ways to measure emotions and conceptualise how one emotion differs from another.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Examples of this include the dimensional models of Russell and others, Plutchik's wheel of emotions, and the general distinction between basic and complex emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Whether scientific method is at all suited for the study of the subjective aspect of emotion, feelings, is a question for philosophy of science and epistemology.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] In practice, the use of self-report (i.e. questionnaires) has been widely adopted by researchers.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Alongside this researchers also use functional magnetic resonance imaging, electroencephalography and physiological measures of skin conductance, muscle tension and hormone secretion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] This hybrid approach should allow researchers to gradually pinpoint the affective phenomenon.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] There are also a few commercial systems available that claim to measure emotions, for instance using automated video analysis or skin conductance (affectiva).
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] A common way to measure the emotions of others is via their emotional expressions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] These include facial expression, vocal expression and bodily posture.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Much work has also gone into coding expressive behavior computer programmes that can be used to read the subject's emotion more reliably.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] The model used for facial expression is the Facial Action Coding System or 'FACS'.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] An influential figure in the development of this system was Paul Ekman.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] For criticism, see the conceptual-act model of emotion.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] These behavioral sources can be contrasted with language descriptive of emotions.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] In both respects one may observe the way that affective display differs from culture to culture.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] The Stanford University Psychology Department has an Affective Science area.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] It emphasizes basic research on emotion, culture, and psychopathology using a broad range of experimental, psychophysiological, neural, and genetic methods to test theory about psychological mechanisms underlying human behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/affective-science] Topics include longevity, culture and emotion, reward processing, depression, social anxiety, risk for psychopathology, and emotion expression, suppression, and dysregulation.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In it, Lockhart-Mummery imagines Britain as it might be in the 25th century using the device of a series of letters home from a New Zealander.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] He imagines a world where all male children are sterilised shortly after birth, except for those carefully selected.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] Those exempt from compulsory sterilisation would provide the "seed" for future generations by artificial insemination.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] The book has 287 pages and begins with a preface followed by a list of 24 chapter titles.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] The foreword is given by the author's friend Lord Horder, president of the Eugenics Society, who thought Lockhart-Mummery's theories radical.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In the book, Lockhart-Mummery imagines Britain as it might be in the 25th century using the device of a series of letters home from a New Zealander.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] His central concern is over-population resulting from man's conquest of the natural world and the risk to man's future from disease or famine.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] He argues that either new sources of food will have to be developed or population will have to be controlled, and for that reason welcomes the increasing use of contraception.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] Lockhart-Mummery envisages government control of reproduction and imagines a world where "all men, except those approximating the ideal citizen" would be sterilised, and women would breed from the remaining stock, in order to produce "perfection".
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In the fourth chapter titled "preferential breeding", he proposes that all male children should be sterilised shortly after birth, except for those carefully selected to exclude "bad hereditary factors".
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] Those exempt from compulsory sterilisation he writes, "will become the fathers of the next generation".
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] If pregnancy does not occur she will be allowed to try again.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] He thought the separation of sexual love from reproduction would have profound social implications for society and possibly give women greater independence.
[src:edward-thorndike/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In the book, he attributes the failure to adopt his policies to "sloppy sentiment" and argues that they will not be adopted until an "autocratic government" arises with the will to act in the interests of all men.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] "***Aktion T4***" (German, pronounced [akˈtsi̯oːn teː fiːɐ]) is the name given to campaigns of mass murder by involuntary euthanasia which targeted people with disabilities and the mentally ill in Nazi Germany.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The term was first used in post-war trials against doctors who had been involved in the killings.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The name T4 is an abbreviation of *Tiergartenstraße* 4, a street address of the Chancellery department set up in early 1940, in the Berlin borough of Tiergarten, which recruited and paid personnel associated with Aktion T4.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Certain German physicians were authorised to select patients "deemed incurably sick, after most critical medical examination" and then administer to them a "mercy death" (*Gnadentod*).
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In October 1939, Adolf Hitler signed a "euthanasia note", backdated to 1 September 1939, which authorised his physician Karl Brandt and *Reichsleiter* Philipp Bouhler to begin the killing.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The killings took place from September 1939 until the end of World War II in Europe in 1945.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Between 275,000 and 300,000 people were killed in psychiatric hospitals in Germany, Austria, occupied Poland, and the Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia (now the Czech Republic).
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The number of victims was originally recorded as 70,273 but this number has been increased by the discovery of victims listed in the archives of the former East Germany.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] About half of those killed were taken from church-run asylums.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In June 1940, Paul Braune and Fritz von Bodelschwingh, who served as directors of sanatoriums, protested against the killings, being members of the Lutheran Confessing Church.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The Holy See announced on 2 December 1940 that the policy was contrary to divine law and that "the direct killing of an innocent person because of mental or physical defects is not allowed".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Several reasons have been suggested for the killings, including eugenics, racial hygiene, and saving money.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Physicians in German and Austrian asylums continued many of the practices of *Aktion T4* until the defeat of Germany in 1945, in spite of its official cessation in August 1941.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The informal continuation of the policy led to 93,521 "beds emptied" by the end of 1941.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Technology developed under *Aktion T4*, particularly the use of lethal gas on large numbers of people, was taken over by the medical division of the Reich Interior Ministry, along with the personnel of *Aktion T4*, who participated in the mass murder of Jewish people under Operation Reinhard.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The number of people killed was about 200,000 in Germany and Austria, with about 100,000 victims in other European countries.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Following the war, a number of the perpetrators were tried and convicted for murder and crimes against humanity.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] At the beginning of the twentieth century, the sterilisation of people carrying what were considered to be hereditary defects and in some cases those exhibiting what was thought to be hereditary "antisocial" behaviour, was a respectable field of medicine.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Canada, Denmark, Switzerland and the United States had passed laws enabling coerced sterilisation.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Studies conducted in the 1920s ranked Germany as a country that was unusually reluctant to introduce sterilisation legislation.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In his book *Mein Kampf* (1924), Hitler wrote that one day racial hygiene "will appear as a deed greater than the most victorious wars of our present bourgeois era".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In July 1933, the "Law for the Prevention of Hereditarily Diseased Offspring" prescribed compulsory sterilisation for people with conditions thought to be hereditary, such as schizophrenia, epilepsy, Huntington's chorea and "imbecility".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Sterilisation was also legalised for chronic alcoholism and other forms of social deviance.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The law was administered by the Interior Ministry under Wilhelm Frick through special Hereditary Health Courts (*Erbgesundheitsgerichte*), which examined the inmates of nursing homes, asylums, prisons, aged-care homes and special schools, to select those to be sterilised.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] It is estimated that 360,000 people were sterilised under this law between 1933 and 1939.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The policy and research agenda of racial hygiene and eugenics were promoted by Emil Kraepelin.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Within the Nazi administration, the idea of including in the programme people with physical disabilities had to be expressed carefully, because the Reich Minister of Propaganda, Joseph Goebbels, had a deformed right leg.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] After 1937, the acute shortage of labour in Germany arising from rearmament, meant that anyone capable of work was deemed to be "useful", exempted from the law and the rate of sterilisation declined.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The term *Aktion T4* is a post-war coining; contemporary German terms included *Euthanasie* (euthanasia) and *Gnadentod* (merciful death).
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The T4 programme stemmed from the Nazi Party policy of "racial hygiene", a belief that the German people needed to be cleansed of "racial enemies," including the mentally ill and disabled.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] New insulin shock treatments were used by German psychiatrists to find out if patients with schizophrenia were curable.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Karl Brandt, Hitler's doctor, and Hans Lammers, the head of the Reich Chancellery, testified after the war that Hitler had told them as early as 1933—when the sterilisation law was passed—that he favoured the killing of the incurably ill but recognised that public opinion would not accept this.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In 1935, Hitler told the Leader of Reich Doctors, Gerhard Wagner, that the question could not be taken up in peacetime; "Such a problem could be more smoothly and easily carried out in war." He wrote that he intended to "radically solve" the problem of the mental asylums in such an event.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] On 18 August 1939, three weeks after the killing of Kretschmar, the *Reich Committee for the Scientific Registering of Hereditary and Congenital Illnesses* was established to register sick children or newborns identified as defective.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The secret killing of infants began in 1939 and increased after the war started.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] By 1941, more than 5,000 children had been killed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler was in favour of killing those whom he judged to be *lebensunwertes Leben* ('Life unworthy of life').
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] This issue, according to the Nazi regime, assumed a new urgency in wartime.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Pfannmüller advocated killing by a gradual decrease of food, which he believed was more merciful than poison injections.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The German eugenics movement had an extreme wing even before the Nazis came to power.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] As early as 1920, Alfred Hoche and Karl Binding advocated killing people whose lives were "unworthy of life" (*lebensunwertes Leben*).
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Darwinism was interpreted by them as justification of the demand for "beneficial" genes and eradication of the "harmful" ones.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Robert Lifton wrote, "The argument went that the best young men died in war, causing a loss to the *Volk* of the best genes.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The genes of those who did not fight (the worst genes) then proliferated freely, accelerating biological and cultural degeneration".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The advocacy of eugenics in Germany gained ground after 1930, when the Depression was used to excuse cuts in funding to state mental hospitals, creating squalor and overcrowding.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Many German eugenicists were nationalists and antisemites, who embraced the Nazi regime with enthusiasm.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Many were appointed to positions in the Health Ministry and German research institutes.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Their ideas were gradually adopted by the majority of the German medical profession, from which Jewish and communist doctors were soon purged.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In the 1930s, the Nazi Party had carried out a campaign of propaganda in favour of euthanasia.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The National Socialist Racial and Political Office (NSRPA) produced leaflets, posters and short films to be shown in cinemas, pointing out to Germans the cost of maintaining asylums for the incurably ill and insane.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Brandt and Bouhler were authorised to approve applications to kill children in relevant circumstances, though Bouhler left the details to subordinates such as Brack and SA-*Oberführer* Werner Blankenburg.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Extermination centres were established at six existing psychiatric hospitals: Bernburg, Brandenburg, Grafeneck, Hadamar, Hartheim, and Sonnenstein.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] One thousand children under the age of 17 were killed at the institutions Am Spiegelgrund and Gugging in Austria.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] They played a crucial role in developments leading to the Holocaust.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] As a related aspect of the "medical" and scientific basis of this programme, the Nazi doctors took thousands of brains from 'euthanasia' victims for research.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] From August 1939, the Interior Ministry registered children with disabilities, requiring doctors and midwives to report all cases of newborns with severe disabilities; the 'guardian' consent element soon disappeared.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The reports were assessed by a panel of medical experts, of whom three were required to give their approval before a child could be killed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The Ministry used deceit when dealing with parents or guardians, particularly in Catholic areas, where parents were generally uncooperative.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Parents were told that their children were being sent to "Special Sections", where they would receive improved treatment.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The children sent to these centres were kept for "assessment" for a few weeks and then killed by injection of toxic chemicals, typically phenol; their deaths were recorded as "pneumonia".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Autopsies were usually performed and brain samples were taken to be used for "medical research".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Post mortem examinations apparently helped to ease the consciences of many of those involved, giving them the feeling that there was a genuine medical purpose to the killings.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The most notorious of these institutions in Austria was Am Spiegelgrund, where from 1940 to 1945, 789 children were killed by lethal injection, gas poisoning and physical abuse.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Children's brains were preserved in jars of formaldehyde and stored in the basement of the clinic and in the private collection of Heinrich Gross, one of the institution's directors, until 2001.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] When the Second World War began in September 1939, less rigorous standards of assessment and a quicker approval process were adopted.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] More pressure was placed on parents to agree to their children being sent away.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Many parents suspected what was happening and refused consent, especially when it became apparent that institutions for children with disabilities were being systematically cleared of their charges.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The parents were warned that they could lose custody of all their children and if that did not suffice, the parents could be threatened with call-up for 'labour duty'.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The last child to be killed under *Aktion T4* was Richard Jenne on 29 May 1945, in the children's ward of the Kaufbeuren-Irsee state hospital in Bavaria, Germany, more than three weeks after US Army troops had occupied the town.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Brandt and Bouhler developed plans to expand the programme of euthanasia to adults.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In July 1939 they held a meeting attended by Conti and Professor Werner Heyde, head of the SS medical department.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] This meeting agreed to arrange a national register of all institutionalised people with mental illnesses or physical disabilities.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The first adults with disabilities to be killed en masse by the Nazi regime were Poles.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] After the invasion on 1 September 1939, adults with disabilities were shot by the SS men of *Einsatzkommando* 16, *Selbstschutz* and *EK-Einmann* under the command of SS-*Sturmbannführer* Rudolf Tröger, overseen by Reinhard Heydrich, during Operation Tannenberg.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] All hospitals and mental asylums of the Wartheland were emptied.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The region was incorporated into Germany and earmarked for resettlement by *Volksdeutsche* following the German conquest of Poland.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In the Danzig (now Gdańsk) area, some 7,000 Polish patients of institutions were shot.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Similar measures were taken in other areas of Poland destined for incorporation into Germany.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In December 1939, *Reichsführer-SS* Heinrich Himmler witnessed one of these gassings, ensuring that this invention would later be put to much wider uses.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The idea of killing adult mental patients soon spread from occupied Poland to adjoining areas of Germany, probably because Nazi Party and SS officers in these areas were most familiar with what was happening in Poland.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] These were the areas where Germans wounded from the Polish campaign were expected to be accommodated, which created a demand for hospital space.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The *Gauleiter* of Pomerania, Franz Schwede-Coburg, sent 1,400 patients from five Pomeranian hospitals to undisclosed locations in occupied Poland, where they were shot.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The *Gauleiter* of East Prussia, Erich Koch, had 1,600 patients killed out of sight.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] More than 8,000 Germans were killed in this initial wave of killings carried out on the orders of local officials, although Himmler certainly knew and approved of them.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The legal basis for the programme was a 1939 letter from Hitler, not a formal "Führer's decree" with the force of law.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler bypassed Conti, the Health Minister and his department, who might have raised questions about the legality of the programme and entrusted it to Bouhler and Brandt.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The killings were administered by Viktor Brack and his staff from *Tiergartenstraße* 4, disguised as the "Charitable Foundation for Cure and Institutional Care" offices which served as the front and was supervised by Bouhler and Brandt.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The officials in charge included Herbert Linden, who had been involved in the child killing programme; Ernst-Robert Grawitz, chief physician of the SS and August Becker, an SS chemist.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The officials selected the doctors who were to carry out the operational part of the programme; based on political reliability as long-term Nazis, professional reputation and sympathy for radical eugenics.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The list included physicians who had proved their worth in the child-killing programme, such as Unger, Heinze and Hermann Pfannmüller.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The recruits were mostly psychiatrists, notably Professor Carl Schneider of Heidelberg, Professor Max de Crinis of Berlin and Professor Paul Nitsche from the Sonnenstein state institution.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Heyde became the operational leader of the programme, succeeded later by Nitsche.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The conditions included schizophrenia, epilepsy, Huntington's chorea, advanced syphilis, senile dementia, paralysis, encephalitis and "terminal neurological conditions generally".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Many doctors and administrators assumed that the reports were to identify inmates who were capable of being drafted for "labour service" and tended to overstate the degree of incapacity of their patients, to protect them from labour conscription.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] When some institutions refused to co-operate, teams of T4 doctors, or Nazi medical students, visited and compiled the lists, sometimes in a haphazard and ideologically motivated way.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In 1940, all Jewish patients were removed from institutions and killed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] As with child inmates, adults were assessed by a panel of experts, working at the *Tiergartenstraße* offices.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The experts were required to make their judgements on the reports, not medical histories or examinations.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Sometimes they dealt with hundreds of reports at a time.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] On each they marked a **+** (death), a **-** (life), or occasionally a **?** meaning that they were unable to decide.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Three "death" verdicts condemned the person and as with reviews of children, the process became less rigorous, the range of conditions considered "unsustainable" grew broader and zealous Nazis further down the chain of command increasingly made decisions on their own initiative.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The first gassings in Germany proper took place in January 1940 at the Brandenburg Euthanasia Centre.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The operation was headed by Brack, who said "the needle belongs in the hand of the doctor".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Bottled pure carbon monoxide gas was used.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] At trials, Brandt described the process as a "major advance in medical history".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In addition to Brandenburg, the killing centres included Grafeneck Castle in Baden-Württemberg (10,824 dead), Schloss Hartheim near Linz in Austria (over 18,000 dead), Sonnenstein in Saxony (15,000 dead), Bernburg in Saxony-Anhalt and Hadamar in Hesse (14,494 dead).
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The same facilities were also used to kill mentally sound prisoners transferred from concentration camps in Germany, Austria and occupied parts of Poland.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Condemned patients were transferred from their institutions to new centres in T4 Charitable Ambulance buses, called the Community Patients Transports Service.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] They were run by teams of SS men wearing white coats, to give it an air of medical care.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] To prevent the families and doctors of the patients from tracing them, the patients were often first sent to transit centres in major hospitals, where they were supposedly assessed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] They were moved again to *special treatment* (*Sonderbehandlung*) centres.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Families were sent letters explaining that owing to wartime regulations, it was not possible for them to visit relatives in these centres.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Most of these patients were killed within 24 hours of arriving at the centres and their bodies cremated.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Some bodies were dissected for medical research whilst others had their gold teeth extracted.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] For every person killed, a death certificate was prepared, giving a false but plausible cause of death.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] This was sent to the family along with an urn of ashes (random ashes, since the victims were cremated *en masse*).
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The preparation of thousands of falsified death certificates took up most of the working day of the doctors who operated the centres.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] During 1940, the centres at Brandenburg, Grafeneck and Hartheim killed nearly 10,000 people each, while another 6,000 were killed at Sonnenstein.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In all, about 35,000 people were killed in T4 operations that year.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Operations at Brandenburg and Grafeneck were wound up at the end of the year, partly because the areas they served had been cleared and partly because of public opposition.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In 1941, however, the centres at Bernburg and Sonnenstein increased their operations, while Hartheim (where Wirth and Franz Stangl were successively commandants) continued as before.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Another 35,000 people were killed before August 1941, when the T4 programme was officially shut down by Hitler.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Even after that date the centres continued to be used to kill concentration camp inmates: eventually some 20,000 people in this category were killed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In 1971, Gitta Sereny conducted interviews with Stangl, who was in prison in Düsseldorf, having been convicted of co-responsibility for killing 900,000 people, while commandant of the Sobibor and Treblinka extermination camps in Poland.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Stangl gave Sereny a detailed account of the operations of the T4 programme based on his time as commandant of the killing facility at the Hartheim institute.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] He described how the inmates of asylums were removed and transported by bus to Hartheim.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Some were in no mental state to know what was happening to them but many were perfectly sane and for them forms of deception were used.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] They were told they were at a special clinic where they would receive improved treatment and were given a brief medical examination on arrival.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] They were induced to enter what appeared to be a shower block, where they were gassed with carbon monoxide.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The ruse was also used at extermination camps.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Some of the victims knew their fate and tried to defend themselves.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The SS functionaries and hospital staff associated with *Aktion T4* in the German Reich were paid from the central office at *Tiergartenstraße* 4 in Berlin from the spring of 1940.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The SS and police from *SS-Sonderkommando Lange* responsible for murdering the majority of patients in the annexed territories of Poland since October 1939, took their salaries from the normal police fund, supervised by the administration of the newly formed *Wartheland* district.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The programme in Germany and occupied Poland was overseen by Heinrich Himmler.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In the German T4 centres there was at least the semblance of legality in keeping records and writing letters.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In Polish psychiatric hospitals no one was left behind.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Killings were inflicted using gas-vans, sealed army bunkers and machine guns; families were not informed about the murdered relatives and the empty wards were handed over to the SS.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] After the official end of the euthanasia programme in 1941, most of the personnel and high-ranking officials, as well as gassing technology and the techniques used to deceive victims, were transferred under the jurisdiction of the national medical division of the Reich Interior Ministry.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Further gassing experiments with the use of mobile gas chambers (*Einsatzwagen*) were conducted at Soldau concentration camp by Herbert Lange following Operation Barbarossa.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Lange was appointed commander of the Chełmno extermination camp in December 1941.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] He was given three gas vans by the Reich Security Main Office (RSHA), converted by the Gaubschat GmbH in Berlin and before February 1942, killed 3,830 Polish Jews and around 4,000 Romani, under the guise of "resettlement".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] After the Wannsee conference, implementation of gassing technology was accelerated by Heydrich.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Beginning in the spring of 1942, three killing factories were built secretly in east-central Poland.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The *SS* officers responsible for the earlier *Aktion T4*, including Wirth, Stangl and Irmfried Eberl, had important roles in the implementation of the "Final Solution" for the next two years.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The first killing centre, equipped with stationary gas chambers, modelled on technology developed under *Aktion T4*, was established at Bełżec in the General Government territory of occupied Poland; the decision preceded the Wannsee Conference of January 1942 by three months.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In January 1939, Brack commissioned a paper from Professor of Moral Theology at the University of Paderborn, Joseph Mayer, on the likely reactions of the churches in the event of a state euthanasia programme being instituted.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Mayer – a longstanding euthanasia advocate – reported that the churches would not oppose such a programme if it was seen to be in the national interest.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Brack showed this paper to Hitler in July and it may have increased his confidence that the "euthanasia" programme would be acceptable to German public opinion.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Notably, when Sereny interviewed Mayer shortly before his death in 1967, he denied that he formally condoned the killing of people with disabilities but no copies of this paper are known to survive.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Some bureaucrats opposed the T4 programme; Lothar Kreyssig, a district judge and member of the Confessing Church, wrote to Justice Minister Franz Gürtner protesting that the action was illegal since no law or formal decree from Hitler had authorised it.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Gürtner replied, "If you cannot recognise the will of the Führer as a source of law, then you cannot remain a judge" and had Kreyssig dismissed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler had a policy of not issuing written instructions for matters which could later be condemned by the international community, but made an exception when he provided Bouhler and Brack with written authority for the T4 programme.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler wrote a confidential letter in October 1939 to overcome opposition within the German state bureaucracy.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler told Bouhler that, "the Führer's Chancellery must under no circumstances be seen to be active in this matter".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Gürtner had to be shown Hitler's letter in August 1940 to gain his co-operation.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In the towns where the killing centres were located, some people saw the inmates arrive in buses, saw smoke from the crematoria chimneys and noticed that the buses were returning empty.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In Hadamar, ashes containing human hair rained down on the town and despite the strictest orders, some of the staff at the killing centres talked about what was going on.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In some cases families could tell that the causes of death in certificates were false, e.g. when a patient was claimed to have died of appendicitis, even though his appendix had been removed some years earlier.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In other cases, families in the same town would receive death certificates on the same day.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In May 1941, the Frankfurt County Court wrote to Gürtner describing scenes in Hadamar, where children shouted in the streets that people were being taken away in buses to be gassed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] During 1940, rumours of what was taking place spread and many Germans withdrew their relatives from asylums and sanatoria to care for them at home, often with great expense and difficulty.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In some places doctors and psychiatrists co-operated with families to have patients discharged or if the families could afford it, transferred them to private clinics beyond the reach of T4.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Other doctors "re-diagnosed" patients so that they no longer met the T4 criteria, which risked exposure when Nazi zealots from Berlin conducted inspections.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In Kiel, Professor Hans Gerhard Creutzfeldt managed to save nearly all of his patients.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Lifton listed a handful of psychiatrists and administrators who opposed the killings; many doctors collaborated, either through ignorance, agreement with Nazi eugenicist policies or fear of the regime.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Protest letters were sent to the Reich Chancellery and the Ministry of Justice, some from Nazi Party members.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The first open protest against the removal of people from asylums took place at Absberg in Franconia in February 1941 and others followed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The SD report on the incident at Absberg noted that "the removal of residents from the Ottilien Home has caused a great deal of unpleasantness" and described large crowds of Catholic townspeople, among them Party members, protesting against the action.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Similar petitions and protests occurred throughout Austria as rumours spread of mass killings at the Hartheim Euthanasia Centre and of mysterious deaths at the children's clinic, *Am Spiegelgrund* in Vienna.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Anna Wödl, a nurse and mother of a child with a disability, vehemently petitioned to Hermann Linden at the Reich Ministry of the Interior in Berlin to prevent her son, Alfred, from being transferred from Gugging, where he lived and which also became a euthanasia center.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Wödl failed and Alfred was sent to *Am Spiegelgrund*, where he was killed on 22 February 1941.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] His brain was preserved in formaldehyde for "research" and stored in the clinic for sixty years.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The Lutheran theologian Friedrich von Bodelschwingh (director of the Bethel Institution for Epilepsy at Bielefeld) and Pastor Paul-Gerhard Braune (director of the Hoffnungstal Institution near Berlin) protested.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Bodelschwingh negotiated directly with Brandt and indirectly with Hermann Göring, whose cousin was a prominent psychiatrist.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Braune had meetings with Gürtner, who was always dubious about the legality of the programme.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Gürtner later wrote a strongly worded letter to Hitler protesting against it; Hitler did not read it but was told about it by Lammers.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] On 4 December 1940, Reinhold Sautter, the Supreme Church Councillor of the Württemberg State Church, complained to the Nazi Ministerial Councillor Eugen Stähle against the murders in Grafeneck Castle.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Stähle said "The fifth commandment Thou shalt not kill, is no commandment of God but a Jewish invention".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Bishop Heinrich Wienken of Berlin, a leading member of the Caritas Association, was selected by the Fulda episcopal synod to represent the views of the Catholic Church in meetings with T4 operatives.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Galen's sermons were not reported in the German press but were circulated illegally in leaflets.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The text was dropped by the Royal Air Force over German troops.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Evans wrote that "This was the strongest, most explicit and most widespread protest movement against any policy since the beginning of the Third Reich".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Local Nazis asked for Galen to be arrested but Goebbels told Hitler that such action would provoke a revolt in Westphalia and Hitler decided to wait until after the war to take revenge.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] In 1986, Lifton wrote, "Nazi leaders faced the prospect of either having to imprison prominent, highly admired clergymen and other protesters – a course with consequences in terms of adverse public reaction they greatly feared – or else end the programme".
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Evans considered it "at least possible, even indeed probable" that the T4 programme would have continued beyond Hitler's initial quota of 70,000 deaths but for the public reaction to Galen's sermon.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Burleigh called assumptions that the sermon affected Hitler's decision to suspend the T4 programme "wishful thinking" and noted that the various Church hierarchies did not complain after the transfer of T4 personnel to *Aktion Reinhard*.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Galen had detailed knowledge of the euthanasia programme by July 1940 but did not speak out until almost a year after Protestants had begun to protest.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] On 29 June 1943, Pope Pius XII issued the encyclical *Mystici corporis Christi*, in which he condemned the fact that "physically deformed people, mentally disturbed people and hereditarily ill people have at times been robbed of their lives" in Germany.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] On 24 August 1941, Hitler ordered the suspension of the T4 killings.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] After the invasion of the Soviet Union in June, many T4 personnel were transferred to the eastern front.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The projected death total for the T4 programme of 70,000 deaths had been reached by August 1941.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The termination of the T4 programme did not end the killing of people with disabilities; from the end of 1941, on the initiative of institute directors and local party leaders, the killing of adults and children continued, albeit less systematically, until the end of the war.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] After the bombing of Hamburg in July 1943, occupants of old age homes were killed.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] Hilda Wernicke, Berlin, August 1946, testimony was given that "500 old, broken women" who had survived the bombing of Stettin in June 1944 were euthanised at the Meseritz-Oberwalde Asylum.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The Hartheim, Bernberg, Sonnenstein and Hadamar centres continued in use as "wild euthanasia" centres to kill people sent from all over Germany, until 1945.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] The methods were lethal injection or starvation, those employed before use of gas chambers.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] By the end of 1941, about 100,000 people had been killed in the T4 programme.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p01] From mid-1941, concentration camp prisoners too feeble or too much trouble to keep alive were murdered after a cursory psychiatric examination under Action 14f13.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] After the war trials were held in connection with the Nazi euthanasia programme at various places including Dresden, Frankfurt, Graz, Nuremberg and Tübingen.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] In December 1946 an American military tribunal (commonly called the Doctors' trial) prosecuted 23 doctors and administrators for their roles in war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] These crimes included the systematic killing of those deemed "unworthy of life", including people with mental disabilities, the people who were institutionalised mentally ill and people with physical impairments.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] After 140 days of proceedings, including the testimony of 85 witnesses and the submission of 1,500 documents, in August 1947 the court pronounced 16 of the defendants guilty.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] Seven were sentenced to death; the men, including Brandt and Brack, were executed on 2 June 1948.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] Earlier, in 1945, American forces tried seven staff members of the Hadamar killing centre for the killing of Soviet and Polish nationals, which was within their jurisdiction under international law, as these were the citizens of wartime allies.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] (Hadamar was within the American Zone of Occupation in Germany.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] This was before the Allied resolution of December 1945, to prosecute individuals for "crimes against humanity" for such mass atrocities.) Alfons Klein, Heinrich Ruoff and Karl Willig were sentenced to death and executed; the other four were given long prison sentences.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] In 1946, reconstructed German courts tried members of the Hadamar staff for the murders of nearly 15,000 German citizens.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] The chief physician, Adolf Wahlmann and Irmgard Huber, the head nurse, were convicted.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] The Stasi (Ministry for State Security) of East Germany stored around 30,000 files of *Aktion T4* in their archives.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] Those files became available to the public after German Reunification in 1990, leading to a new wave of research on these wartime crimes.
[src:edward-thorndike/aktion-t4-p02] The German national memorial to the people with disabilities murdered by the Nazis was dedicated in 2014 in Berlin.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike was a member of the board of the Psychological Corporation and served as president of the American Psychological Association in 1912.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] A *Review of General Psychology* survey, published in 2002, ranked Thorndike as the ninth-most cited psychologist of the 20th century.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Edward Thorndike had a powerful impact on reinforcement theory and behavior analysis, providing the basic framework for empirical laws in behavior psychology with his law of effect.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Through his contributions to the behavioral psychology field came his major impacts on education, where the law of effect has great influence in the classroom.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike, born in Williamsburg, Massachusetts was the son of Edward R and Abbie B Thorndike, a Methodist minister in Lowell, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike graduated from The Roxbury Latin School (1891), in West Roxbury, Massachusetts and from Wesleyan University (B.S.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He earned an M.A. at Harvard University in 1897.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His two brothers (Lynn and Ashley) also became important scholars.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The younger, Lynn, was a medievalist specializing in the history of science and magic, while the older, Ashley, was an English professor and noted authority on Shakespeare.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] While at Harvard, he was interested in how animals learn (ethology), and worked with William James.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Afterwards, he became interested in the animal 'man', to the study of which he then devoted his life.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Edward's thesis is sometimes thought of as the essential document of modern comparative psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Upon graduation, Thorndike returned to his initial interest, educational psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In 1898 he completed his PhD at Columbia University under the supervision of James McKeen Cattell, one of the founding fathers of psychometrics.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In 1937 Thorndike became the second President of the Psychometric Society, following in the footsteps of Louis Leon Thurstone who had established the society and its journal Psychometrika the previous year.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] On August 29, 1900, he wed Elizabeth Moulton.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] They had five children, among them Frances, who became a mathematician.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] During the early stages of his career, he purchased a wide tract of land on the Hudson and encouraged other researchers to settle around him.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Soon a colony had formed there with him as its 'tribal' chief.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike was a pioneer not only in behaviorism and in studying learning, but also in using animals in clinical experiments.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike was able to create a theory of learning based on his research with animals.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His doctoral dissertation, "Animal Intelligence: An Experimental Study of the Associative Processes in Animals", was the first in psychology where the subjects were nonhumans.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike was interested in whether animals could learn tasks through imitation or observation.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] To test this, Thorndike created puzzle boxes.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The puzzle boxes were approximately 20 inches long, 15 inches wide, and 12 inches tall.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Each box had a door that was pulled open by a weight attached to a string that ran over a pulley and was attached to the door.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The string attached to the door led to a lever or button inside the box.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] When the animal pressed the bar or pulled the lever, the string attached to the door would cause the weight to lift and the door to open.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's puzzle boxes were arranged so that the animal would be required to perform a certain response (pulling a lever or pushing a button), while he measured the amount of time it took them to escape.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Once the animal had performed the desired response they were allowed to escape and were also given a reward, usually food.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike primarily used cats in his puzzle boxes.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] When the cats were put into the cages they would wander restlessly and meow, but they did not know how to escape.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Eventually, the cats would step on the switch on the floor by chance, and the door would open.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] To see if the cats could learn through observation, he had them observe other animals escaping from the box.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He would then compare the times of those who got to observe others escaping with those who did not, and he found that there was no difference in their rate of learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike saw the same results with other animals, and he observed that there was no improvement even when he placed the animals' paws on the correct levers, buttons, or bar.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] These failures led him to fall back on a trial and error explanation of learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He found that after accidentally stepping on the switch once, they would press the switch faster in each succeeding trial inside the puzzle box.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] By observing and recording the animals' escapes and escape times, Thorndike was able to graph the times it took for the animals in each trial to escape, resulting in a learning curve.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The animals had difficulty escaping at first, but eventually "caught on" and escaped faster and faster with each successive puzzle box trial, until they eventually leveled off.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The quickened rate of escape results in the s-shape of the learning curve.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The learning curve also suggested that different species learned in the same way but at different speeds.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] From his research with puzzle boxes, Thorndike was able to create his own theory of learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The puzzle box experiments were motivated in part by Thorndike's dislike for statements that animals made use of extraordinary faculties such as insight in their problem solving: "In the first place, most of the books do not give us a psychology, but rather a eulogy of animals.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike meant to distinguish clearly whether or not cats escaping from puzzle boxes were using insight.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's instruments in answering this question were learning curves revealed by plotting the time it took for an animal to escape the box each time it was in the box.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He reasoned that if the animals were showing insight, then their time to escape would suddenly drop to a negligible period, which would also be shown in the learning curve as an abrupt drop; while animals using a more ordinary method of trial and error would show gradual curves.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His finding was that cats consistently showed gradual learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike put his testing expertise to work for the United States Army during World War I, participating in the development of the Army Beta test used to evaluate illiterate, unschooled, and non-English speaking recruits.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike believed that "Instruction should pursue specified, socially useful goals." Thorndike believed that the ability to learn did not decline until age 35, and only then at a rate of 1 percent per year.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike also stated the law of effect, which says behaviors that are followed by good consequences are likely to be repeated in the future.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike identified the three main areas of intellectual development.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] This is the ability to process and understand different concepts.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The second is mechanical intelligence, which is the ability to handle physical objects.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] This is the ability to handle human interaction.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Law of effect– if an association is followed by a "satisfying state of affairs" it will be strengthened and if it is followed by an "annoying state of affairs " it will be weakened.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's law of exercise has two parts; the law of use and the law of disuse.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Law of disuse– the longer an association is unused the weaker it becomes.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Law of recency– the most recent response is most likely to reoccur.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Multiple response– problem solving through trial and error.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] An animal will try multiple responses if the first response does not lead to a specific state of affairs.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Set or attitude– animals are predisposed to act in a specific way.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Prepotency of elements– a subject can filter out irrelevant aspects of a problem and focus and respond only to significant elements of a problem.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Response by analogy– responses from a related or similar context may be used in a new context.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Identical elements theory of transfer– This theory states that the extent to which information learned in one situation will transfer to another situation is determined by the similarity between the two situations.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The more similar the situations are, the greater the amount of information that will transfer.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Similarly, if the situations have nothing in common, information learned in one situation will not be of any value in the other situation.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Associative shifting– it is possible to shift any response from occurring with one stimulus to occurring with another stimulus.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Associative shift maintains that a response is first made to situation A, then to AB, and then finally to B, thus shifting a response from one condition to another by associating it with that condition.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Law of readiness– a quality in responses and connections that results in readiness to act.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike acknowledges that responses may differ in their readiness.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He claims that eating has a higher degree of readiness than vomiting, that weariness detracts from the readiness to play and increases the readiness to sleep.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Also, Thorndike argues that a low or negative status in respect to readiness is called unreadiness.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Behavior and learning are influenced by the readiness or unreadiness of responses, as well as by their strength.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Identifiability– According to Thorndike, the identification or placement of a situation is a first response of the nervous system, which can recognize it.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Then connections may be made to one another or to another response, and these connections depend upon the original identification.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Therefore, a large amount of learning is made up of changes in the identifiability of situations.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike also believed that analysis might turn situations into compounds of features, such as the number of sides on a shape, to help the mind grasp and retain the situation, and increase their identifiability.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Availability– The ease of getting a specific response.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] For example, it would be easier for a person to learn to touch their nose or mouth than it would be for them to draw a line 5 inches long with their eyes closed.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's research focused on instrumental learning, which means that learning is developed from the organism doing something.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] For example, he placed a cat inside a wooden box.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The cat would use various methods while trying to get out, but nothing would work until it hit the lever.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Afterwards, Thorndike tried placing the cat inside the wooden box again.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] This time, the cat was able to hit the lever quickly and succeeded in getting out from the box.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] At first, Thorndike emphasized the importance of dissatisfaction stemming from failure as equal to the reward of satisfaction with success, though in his experiments and trials on humans he came to conclude that reward is a much more effective motivator than punishment.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He also emphasized that the satisfaction must come immediately after the success, or the lesson would not sink in.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He argued that "selective breeding can alter man's capacity to learn, to keep sane, to cherish justice or to be happy.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's Educational psychology began a trend toward behavioral psychology that sought to use empirical evidence and a scientific approach to problem solving.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike was among some of the first psychologists to combine learning theory, psychometrics, and applied research for school-related subjects to form psychology of education.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] One of his influences on education is seen by his ideas on mass marketing of tests and textbooks at that time.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike opposed the idea that learning should reflect nature, which was the main thought of developmental scientists at that time.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He instead thought that schooling should improve upon nature.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Unlike many other psychologist of his time, Thorndike took a statistical approach to education in his later years by collecting qualitative information intended to help teachers and educators deal with practical educational problems.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's theory was an association theory, as many were in that time.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He believed that the association between stimulus and response was solidified by a reward or confirmation.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He also thought that motivation was an important factor in learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The Law of Effect introduced the relation between reinforcers and punishers.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Although Thorndike's description of the relation between reinforcers and punishers was incomplete, his work in this area would later become a catalyst in further research, such as that of B.F.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's Law of Effect states that "responses that produce a desired effect are more likely to occur again whereas responses that produce an unpleasant effect are less likely to occur again".
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The terms 'desired effect' and 'unpleasant effect' eventually became known as 'reinforcers' and 'punishers'.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's contributions to the Behavioral Psychology Society are seen through his influences in the classroom, with a particular focus on praising and ignoring behaviors.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Praise is used in the classroom to encourage and support the occurrence of a desired behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] When used in the classroom, praise has been shown to increase correct responses and appropriate behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Planned ignoring is used to decrease, weaken, or eliminate the occurrence of a target behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Planned ignoring is accomplished by removing the reinforcer that is maintaining the behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] For example, when the teacher does not pay attention to a "whining" behavior of a student, it allows the student to realize that whining will not succeed in gaining the attention of the teacher.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Unlike later behaviorists such as John B.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Watson, who placed a very strong emphasis on the impact of environmental influences on behavior, Thorndike believed that differences in the parental behavior of men and women were due to biological, rather than cultural, reasons.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Indeed, Watson himself overtly critiqued the idea of maternal instincts in humans in a report of his observations of first-time mothers struggling to breastfeed.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's beliefs about inborn differences between the thoughts and behavior of men and women included arguments about the role of women in society.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike composed three different word books to assist teachers with word and reading instruction.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] After publication of *The Teacher's Word Book* in 1921, two other books were written and published, each approximately a decade apart from its predecessor.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In Appendix A to the second book, Thorndike gives credit to his word counts and how frequencies were assigned to particular words.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Some words require more emphasis than others, and, according to Thorndike, his list informs teachers of the most frequently occurring words that should be reinforced by instruction and thus become "a permanent part of [students'] stock of word knowledge" (p. xi).
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] If a word is not on the list but appears in an educational text, its meaning only needs to be understood temporarily in the context in which it was found, and then summarily discarded from memory.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike contributed a great deal to psychology.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His influence on animal psychologists, especially those who focused on behavior plasticity, greatly contributed to the future of that field.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In addition to helping pave the way towards behaviorism, his contribution to measurement influenced philosophy, the administration and practice of education, military administration, industrial personnel administration, civil service and many public and private social services.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike influenced many schools of psychology as Gestalt psychologists, psychologists studying the conditioned reflex, and behavioral psychologists all studied Thorndike's research as a starting point.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] However, unlike Watson, Thorndike introduced the concept of reinforcement.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike was the first to apply psychological principles to the area of learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His research led to many theories and laws of learning.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His theory of learning, especially the law of effect, is most often considered to be his greatest achievement.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In 1929, Thorndike addressed his early theory of learning, and claimed that he had been wrong.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] After further research, he was forced to denounce his law of exercise completely, because he found that practice alone did not strengthen an association, and that time alone did not weaken an association.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He also got rid of half of the law of effect, after finding that a satisfying state of affairs strengthens an association, but punishment is not effective in modifying behavior.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He placed a great emphasis on consequences of behavior as setting the foundation for what is and is not learned.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His work represents the transition from the school of functionalism to behaviorism, and enabled psychology to focus on learning theory.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's work would eventually be a major influence to B.F.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Skinner, like Thorndike, put animals in boxes and observed them to see what they were able to learn.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The learning theories of Thorndike and Pavlov were later synthesized by Clark Hull.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His work on motivation and attitude formation directly affected studies on human nature as well as social order.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's research drove comparative psychology for fifty years, and influenced countless psychologists over that period of time, and even still today.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In 1912, Thorndike was elected president for the American Psychological Association.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] In 1917 he was elected as a Fellow of the American Statistical Association.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He was admitted to the National Academy of Sciences in 1917.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He was one of the first psychologists to be admitted to the association.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike is well known for his experiments on animals supporting the law of effect.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1932 and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1934.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] That same year, Thorndike was elected president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Thorndike's connectionism has been criticized for being too simplistic and reductionistic.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] His law of effect and puzzle box methodology were subjected to detailed criticism by behaviorists and many other psychologists.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] The criticisms over the law of effect mostly cover four aspects of the theory: the implied or retroactive working of the effect, the philosophical implication of the law, the identification of the effective conditions that cause learning, and the comprehensive usefulness of the law.
[src:edward-thorndike/edward-thorndike] Because of his "racist, sexist, and antisemitic ideals", amid the George Floyd protests of 2020, the Board of Trustees of Teachers' College in New York voted unanimously to remove his name from Thorndike Hall.
